{"title_page": "Richard Weller", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=December 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n\n'''Richard Weller''' is an Australian [[landscape architect]] and [[academia|academic]]. He is Professor and Chair of Landscape Architecture at the [[University of Pennsylvania]] in [[Philadelphia]], having succeeded [[James Corner]] in 2013.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.upenn.edu/almanac/volumes/v59/n17/weller.html|title=Landscape Architecture Department at Penn Design: Richard Weller|publisher=University of Pennsylvania|volume=59|number=17|date=January 15, 2013}}</ref> Weller also holds the Martin and Margy Meyerson Chair of Urbanism at the University of Pennsylvania,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.design.upenn.edu/landscape-architecture/people/richard-weller-0|title=Landscape Architecture {{!}} PennDesign|website=www.design.upenn.edu|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref> is on the Board of Directors of the Landscape Architecture Foundation, Washington D.C.,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lafoundation.org/about/board-of-directors/|title=Board of Directors {{!}} Landscape Architecture Foundation|website=lafoundation.org|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref> and is Creative Director of the award-winning ''LA+ Interdisciplinary Journal of Landscape Architecture''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://laplusjournal.com/ABOUT|title=ABOUT - laplusjournal|website=laplusjournal.com|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref> He was formerly a Winthrop Professor of Landscape Architecture at the [[University of Western Australia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://research-repository.uwa.edu.au/en/persons/richard-weller|title=Richard Weller|publisher=University of Western Australia|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref> and director of the Australian Urban Design Research Centre (AUDRC).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://streetfurniture.com/au/profile-richard-weller/|title=In Profile: Richard Weller|publisher=Street Furniture|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.uwa.edu.au/201012223201/arts-and-culture/leading-landscape-architect-richard-weller-head-urban-design-centre|title=Leading landscape architect Richard Weller to head Urban Design Centre|publisher=University of Western Australia|date=22 December 2010|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref> He has received a number of awards for teaching excellence including a 2012 national citation \"for sustained commitment to inspiring and enabling students to engage creatively and critically with complex design problems\".<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20121223013249/http://www.olt.gov.au/system/files/2012_OLT_Citation_Recipients_and_citation.pdf</ref> In 2017, and again in 2018, Weller was named by DesignIntelligence as one of the \"25 most-admired educators\" based on a comprehensive survey across the US design industry. \u201cWeller demonstrates an intense engagement and commitment to students\u2019 academic and professional careers,\u201d according to the report. \u201cHe is advancing the profession through a critical look at past and current issues in ecology and design . . . shows humility and humanity in a challenging profession, and has the ability to always call us back to the biggest ideas that design needs to address.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.design.upenn.edu/landscape-architecture/post/richard-weller-among-\u2018most-admired-educators\u2019-landscape-architecture|title=Richard Weller Among \u2018Most Admired Educators\u2019 in Landscape Architecture|publisher=University of Pennsylvania|date=27 September 2017|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.architecturalrecord.com/articles/13611-top-architecture-schools-of-2019|title=Top Architecture Schools of 2019|author=David Gilmore|magazine=Architectural Record|date=4 September 2018|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref> In 2020, Weller was inducted into the Academy of Fellows of the Council of Educators in Landscape Architecture (CELA). <ref>https://www.design.upenn.edu/landscape-architecture/post/cela-2020-awardees-announced?mc_cid=7df45e20c5&mc_eid=c4ff0c8bcd</ref> \n\n==Works==\nWeller is a landscape architect and former co-director (with [[Vladimir Sitta]]) of [[Australia]]n landscape architecture firm Room 4.1.3. whose built projects include the \"Garden of Australian Dreams\"<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20070904105709/http://www.aila.org.au/projects/ACT/goad/article02.htm</ref> at the [[National Museum of Australia]] in [[Canberra]], [[Australian Capital Territory|ACT]]. The built garden attracted controversy for its radical design.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/gough-splutter-museums-blue-poles-cause-a-whole-new-row-20031212-gdwx47.html|title=Gough! Splutter! Museum's blue poles cause a whole new row|work=[[The Age]]|date=12 December 2003|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Edward Elgar|url=http://www.copyright.bbk.ac.uk/contents/publications/workshops/theme3/rimmerpaper.pdf|title=The garden of Australian Dreams: The Moral Rights of Landscape Architects|publisher=ACIPA}}</ref> He is also identified as a major proponent for the [[Elizabeth Quay]] project in [[Perth, Western Australia]], and this can be found in the contents of ''Boomtown'' where he uses quotes from various supporters and detractors of the project.<ref>{{cite book|author=Weller, Richard|title=Boomtown 2050 : scenarios for a rapidly growing city|year=2009|publisher=UWA Publishing|edition=1st|isbn=978-1-921401-21-3}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://insidestory.org.au/trouble-in-the-city/|title=Trouble in the city|author=Peter Spearritt|publisher=Inside Story|date=22 October 2009|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nWeller's design work has been exhibited in the Museum of Contemporary Art in [[Sydney]] (1998) as a finalist in the Seppelt Australian Art Awards.<ref>{{cite book|author=Michael, Linda|title=Seppelt Contemporary Art Awards 1998|year=1998|publisher=Museum of Contemporary Art|isbn=978-1-875632-63-3}}</ref> His work has also been exhibited in the Venice Biennale (2004), the MAXXI Gallery in Rome (2016), the [[Isabella Stewart Gardner Museum]] in Boston (2017), the Canadian Design Museum in Toronto (2018), and the [[Guggenheim Museum]] in New York (2020) as part of the \"Countryside, The Future\" exhibition curated by Rem Koolhaas. Weller is an invited participant in the 2020 [[Venice Biennale]] di Architettura curated by Hashim Sarkis.<ref>https://www.labiennale.org/en/news/biennale-architettura-2020-how-will-we-live-together</ref> <ref>https://www.labiennale.org/en/architecture/2020/participants</ref>\n\nIn 2002 Weller's design was selected as a finalist in the [[Pentagon Memorial]] competition in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://competitions.org/?option=com_content&view=article&id=125%3Apentagon-memorial-competition-&Itemid=63|title=A Pean to its Founders in Weimar New Bauhaus Museum Commemorates an Anniversary|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref> and in 2005 he was a finalist in the Tsunami Memorial competition in [[Thailand]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theage.com.au/world/field-of-lights-in-tsunami-memorial-bid-20060503-gdngwg.html|title=Field of lights in tsunami memorial bid|work=The Age|date=3 May 2006|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref> His early work (1990 to 1995) as consultant to Berlin landscape architecture firm Muller, Knippschild Wehberg (now L\u00fctzow 7) was heavily awarded in European design competitions.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Weller, Richard|title=Room 4.1.3: Innovations in Landscape Architecture|year=2005|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|edition=1st|isbn=0-8122-3784-6}}</ref>\n\n==Research and Publications==\nWeller gave the Frederick Law Olmsted Memorial Lecture at the Harvard Graduate School of Design in 2011<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gsd.harvard.edu/event/frederick-law-olmsted-lecture-richard-weller-zoomscape-x5/|title=Frederick Law Olmsted Lecture: Richard Weller, \u201cZOOMSCAPE X5\u201d|publisher=Harvard University|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref>, and many invited lectures and addresses including at Milano Architecture Week (Milan, 2019),<ref>https://us2.campaign-archive.com/?u=4d29cc62d167dea835ce55013&id=6f14fd214d</ref> the first World Forum on Urban Forests (Mantova, 2018),<ref>https://www.wfuf2018.com/public/file/programmascientificoesecutivoweb1-25613.pdf</ref> and to the UN Secretariat of the Convention on Biological Diversity (Montreal, 2017). He is a regular commentator on planning and design issues.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/bridging-the-future-planning-gap-35-million-become-the-lost-souls-20121123-29ytw.html|author=Catherine Armitage|title=Bridging the future planning gap: 35 million become the 'lost souls'|date=24 November 2012|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Housing the masses as Perth doubles in size|url=http://www.abc.net.au/stateline/wa/content/2006/s2185587.htm|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|date=10 March 2008|accessdate=10 May 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100110203044/http://www.abc.net.au/stateline/wa/content/2006/s2185587.htm|archivedate=10 January 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> He is author of seven books and over 100 single-authored papers. His publications include:\n*''Room 4.1.3: Innovations in Landscape Architecture'' (University of Pennsylvania Press, 2005)<ref>{{cite book|author=Weller, Richard| title=Room 4.1.3: Innovations in Landscape Architecture|year=2005|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|edition=1st|isbn=0-8122-3784-6}}</ref> \n*\"An Art of Instrumentality: Thinking Through Landscape Urbanism\" in Charles Waldheim (ed), ''The Landscape Urbanism Reader'' (Princeton Architectural Press, 2006)\n*''Boomtown 2050: Scenarios for a Rapidly Growing City'' (University of Western Australia Press, 2009)<ref>{{cite book|author=Weller, Richard|title=Boomtown 2050: scenarios for a rapidly growing city|year=2009|publisher=UWA Publishing|edition=1st|isbn=978-1-921401-21-3}}</ref>  \n*''Made in Australia: The Future of Australian Cities'' (UWA Publishing, 2013)<ref>{{cite book|author=Weller, Richard|title=Made in Australia: The Future of Australian Cities|year=2013|publisher=UWA Publishing|edition=1st|isbn=978-1-742584-92-8}}</ref>  \n*''The Atlas for the End of the World'' (2017), an ASLA award-winning website which audits the status of land use and urbanization in the most critically endangered bioregions on Earth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://atlas-for-the-end-of-the-world.com|title=Atlas for the End of the World|website=atlas-for-the-end-of-the-world.com|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n*''Design with Nature Now'' (Lincoln Institute of Land Policy, 2019).<ref>https://www.lincolninst.edu/publications/books/design-nature-now</ref>\n*''Beautiful China: Reflections on Landscape Architecture in Contemporary China'' (ORO Editions, 2020).<ref>https://www.oroeditions.com/product/beautiful-china/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weller, Richard}}\n[[Category:Architects from Western Australia]]\n[[Category:People from Perth, Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=December 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n\n'''Richard Weller''' is an Australian [[landscape architect]] and [[academia|academic]]. He is Professor and Chair of Landscape Architecture at the [[University of Pennsylvania]] in [[Philadelphia]], having succeeded [[James Corner]] in 2013.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.upenn.edu/almanac/volumes/v59/n17/weller.html|title=Landscape Architecture Department at Penn Design: Richard Weller|publisher=University of Pennsylvania|volume=59|number=17|date=January 15, 2013}}</ref> Weller also holds the Martin and Margy Meyerson Chair of Urbanism at the University of Pennsylvania,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.design.upenn.edu/landscape-architecture/people/richard-weller-0|title=Landscape Architecture {{!}} PennDesign|website=www.design.upenn.edu|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref> is on the Board of Directors of the Landscape Architecture Foundation, Washington D.C.,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lafoundation.org/about/board-of-directors/|title=Board of Directors {{!}} Landscape Architecture Foundation|website=lafoundation.org|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref> and is Creative Director of the award-winning ''LA+ Interdisciplinary Journal of Landscape Architecture''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://laplusjournal.com/ABOUT|title=ABOUT - laplusjournal|website=laplusjournal.com|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref> He has been Winthrop Professor of Landscape Architecture at the [[University of Western Australia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://research-repository.uwa.edu.au/en/persons/richard-weller|title=Richard Weller|publisher=University of Western Australia|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref> and director of the Australian Urban Design Research Centre (AUDRC).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://streetfurniture.com/au/profile-richard-weller/|title=In Profile: Richard Weller|publisher=Street Furniture|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.uwa.edu.au/201012223201/arts-and-culture/leading-landscape-architect-richard-weller-head-urban-design-centre|title=Leading landscape architect Richard Weller to head Urban Design Centre|publisher=University of Western Australia|date=22 December 2010|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref> He has received a number of awards for teaching excellence including a 2012 national citation \"for sustained commitment to inspiring and enabling students to engage creatively and critically with complex design problems\".<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20121223013249/http://www.olt.gov.au/system/files/2012_OLT_Citation_Recipients_and_citation.pdf</ref> In 2017, and again in 2018, Weller was named by DesignIntelligence as one of the \"25 most-admired educators\" based on a comprehensive survey across the US design industry. \u201cWeller demonstrates an intense engagement and commitment to students\u2019 academic and professional careers,\u201d according to the report. \u201cHe is advancing the profession through a critical look at past and current issues in ecology and design . . . shows humility and humanity in a challenging profession, and has the ability to always call us back to the biggest ideas that design needs to address.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.design.upenn.edu/landscape-architecture/post/richard-weller-among-\u2018most-admired-educators\u2019-landscape-architecture|title=Richard Weller Among \u2018Most Admired Educators\u2019 in Landscape Architecture|publisher=University of Pennsylvania|date=27 September 2017|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.architecturalrecord.com/articles/13611-top-architecture-schools-of-2019|title=Top Architecture Schools of 2019|author=David Gilmore|magazine=Architectural Record|date=4 September 2018|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\nWeller is a landscape architect and former co-director (with [[Vladimir Sitta]]) of [[Australia]]n landscape architecture firm Room 4.1.3. whose built projects include the \"Garden of Australian Dreams\"<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20070904105709/http://www.aila.org.au/projects/ACT/goad/article02.htm</ref> at the [[National Museum of Australia]] in [[Canberra]], [[Australian Capital Territory|ACT]]. The built garden attracted controversy for its radical design.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/gough-splutter-museums-blue-poles-cause-a-whole-new-row-20031212-gdwx47.html|title=Gough! Splutter! Museum's blue poles cause a whole new row|work=[[The Age]]|date=12 December 2003|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Edward Elgar|url=http://www.copyright.bbk.ac.uk/contents/publications/workshops/theme3/rimmerpaper.pdf|title=The garden of Australian Dreams: The Moral Rights of Landscape Architects|publisher=ACIPA}}</ref> He is also identified as a major proponent for the [[Elizabeth Quay]] project in [[Perth, Western Australia]], and this can be found in the contents of ''Boomtown'' where he uses quotes from various supporters and detractors of the project.<ref>{{cite book|author=Weller, Richard|title=Boomtown 2050 : scenarios for a rapidly growing city|year=2009|publisher=UWA Publishing|edition=1st|isbn=978-1-921401-21-3}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://insidestory.org.au/trouble-in-the-city/|title=Trouble in the city|author=Peter Spearritt|publisher=Inside Story|date=22 October 2009|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nWeller's design work has been exhibited in the Museum of Contemporary Art in [[Sydney]] (1998) as a finalist in the Seppelt Australian Art Awards.<ref>{{cite book|author=Michael, Linda|title=Seppelt Contemporary Art Awards 1998|year=1998|publisher=Museum of Contemporary Art|isbn=978-1-875632-63-3}}</ref> His work has also been exhibited in the Venice Biennale (2004), the MAXXI Gallery in Rome (2016), the [[Isabella Stewart Gardner Museum]] in Boston (2017), the Canadian Design Museum in Toronto (2018), the [[Guggenheim Museum]] in New York (2020) as part of the \"Countryside, The Future\" exhibition curated by Rem Koolhaas, and the [[Venice Biennale]] di Architettura (2020).<ref>https://www.labiennale.org/en/news/biennale-architettura-2020-how-will-we-live-together</ref> \n\nIn 2002 Weller's design was selected as a finalist in the [[Pentagon Memorial]] competition in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://competitions.org/?option=com_content&view=article&id=125%3Apentagon-memorial-competition-&Itemid=63|title=A Pean to its Founders in Weimar New Bauhaus Museum Commemorates an Anniversary|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref> and in 2005 he was a finalist in the Tsunami Memorial competition in [[Thailand]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theage.com.au/world/field-of-lights-in-tsunami-memorial-bid-20060503-gdngwg.html|title=Field of lights in tsunami memorial bid|work=The Age|date=3 May 2006|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref> His early work (1990 to 1995) as consultant to Berlin landscape architecture firm Muller, Knippschild Wehberg (now L\u00fctzow 7) was heavily awarded in European design competitions.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Weller, Richard|title=Room 4.1.3: Innovations in Landscape Architecture|year=2005|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|edition=1st|isbn=0-8122-3784-6}}</ref>\n\n==Research and Publications==\nWeller gave the Frederick Law Olmsted Memorial Lecture at the Harvard Graduate School of Design in 2011<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gsd.harvard.edu/event/frederick-law-olmsted-lecture-richard-weller-zoomscape-x5/|title=Frederick Law Olmsted Lecture: Richard Weller, \u201cZOOMSCAPE X5\u201d|publisher=Harvard University|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref>, and many invited lectures and addresses including at Milano Architecture Week (Milan, 2019),<ref>https://us2.campaign-archive.com/?u=4d29cc62d167dea835ce55013&id=6f14fd214d</ref> the first World Forum on Urban Forests (Mantova, 2018),<ref>https://www.wfuf2018.com/public/file/programmascientificoesecutivoweb1-25613.pdf</ref> and to the UN Secretariat of the Convention on Biological Diversity (Montreal, 2017). He is a regular commentator on planning and design issues.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/bridging-the-future-planning-gap-35-million-become-the-lost-souls-20121123-29ytw.html|author=Catherine Armitage|title=Bridging the future planning gap: 35 million become the 'lost souls'|date=24 November 2012|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Housing the masses as Perth doubles in size|url=http://www.abc.net.au/stateline/wa/content/2006/s2185587.htm|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|date=10 March 2008|accessdate=10 May 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100110203044/http://www.abc.net.au/stateline/wa/content/2006/s2185587.htm|archivedate=10 January 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> He is author of seven books and over 100 single-authored papers. His publications include:\n*''Room 4.1.3: Innovations in Landscape Architecture'' (University of Pennsylvania Press, 2005)<ref>{{cite book|author=Weller, Richard| title=Room 4.1.3: Innovations in Landscape Architecture|year=2005|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|edition=1st|isbn=0-8122-3784-6}}</ref> \n*\"An Art of Instrumentality: Thinking Through Landscape Urbanism\" in Charles Waldheim (ed), ''The Landscape Urbanism Reader'' (Princeton Architectural Press, 2006)\n*''Boomtown 2050: Scenarios for a Rapidly Growing City'' (University of Western Australia Press, 2009)<ref>{{cite book|author=Weller, Richard|title=Boomtown 2050: scenarios for a rapidly growing city|year=2009|publisher=UWA Publishing|edition=1st|isbn=978-1-921401-21-3}}</ref>  \n*''Made in Australia: The Future of Australian Cities'' (UWA Publishing, 2013)<ref>{{cite book|author=Weller, Richard|title=Made in Australia: The Future of Australian Cities|year=2013|publisher=UWA Publishing|edition=1st|isbn=978-1-742584-92-8}}</ref>  \n*''The Atlas for the End of the World'' (2017), an ASLA award-winning website which audits the status of land use and urbanization in the most critically endangered bioregions on Earth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://atlas-for-the-end-of-the-world.com|title=Atlas for the End of the World|website=atlas-for-the-end-of-the-world.com|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n*''Design with Nature Now'' (Lincoln Institute of Land Policy, 2019).<ref>https://www.lincolninst.edu/publications/books/design-nature-now</ref>\n*''Beautiful China: Reflections on Landscape Architecture in Contemporary China'' (ORO Editions, 2020).<ref>https://www.oroeditions.com/product/beautiful-china/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weller, Richard}}\n[[Category:Architects from Western Australia]]\n[[Category:People from Perth, Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Podelaterre", "label": "safe", "comment": "add award sources", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Weller"}
{"title_page": "Angst in My Pants", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Angst In My Pants\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Sparks (band)|Sparks]]\n| cover      = Angst in My Pants - Sparks.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 29 March 1982\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Musicland Studios]]<br><small>([[Munich]], [[West Germany]])</small>\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Rock music|Rock]]<ref name=\"recordcollectormag.com\">{{cite web|url=https://recordcollectormag.com/articles/sparks-456|title=Sparks - Record Collector Magazine|website=recordcollectormag.com|accessdate=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n*[[power pop]]<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/>\n*[[synth-pop]]<ref name=\"recordcollectormag.com\"/>\n}}\n| length     = 35:31\n| label      = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| producer   = [[Reinhold Mack|Mack]]\n| prev_title = [[Whomp That Sucker]]\n| prev_year  = 1981\n| next_title = [[In Outer Space]]\n| next_year  = 1983\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Angst in My Pants\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[I Predict]]\" b/w \"Moustache\n | single1date = April 1982\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic\">[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r18589|pure_url=yes}} Allmusic review]</ref>\n}}<!-- Automatically generated by DASHBot-->\n'''''Angst in My Pants''''' is the eleventh [[studio album]] by the American [[rock music|rock]] band [[Sparks (band)|Sparks]]. The album was released by [[Atlantic Records]] in both the US and UK, and this was the 6th overall label that the band was signed to in the US, and, for the first time since the mid-1970s, the band would be signed the same label in both the US and UK for 3 consecutive albums.\n\n== History ==\n''Angst in My Pants'' marked the second occasion that [[Ron Mael]] and [[Russell Mael]] worked with the backing band of guitarist Bob Haag, bassist [[Leslie Bohem]], and drummer David Kendrick. Additionally James Goodwin augmented the line up playing synthesizers, though these were mixed farther back, letting the rest of the band come to the fore. The resulting [[power pop]]<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> album was recorded at [[Musicland_Studios | Musicland Studios]], Munich, produced by [[Reinhold Mack|Mack]] in association with Giorgio Moroder Enterprises. The recording of the album was the second and last time that Sparks worked with Mack.\n\n== Release ==\n''Angst in My Pants'' was not a success in the UK but was as successful as their former album, ''[[Whomp That Sucker]]'', in the US. It reached #173 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref name=allmusic>{{cite web|url= {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p5494/charts-awards/billboard-albums|pure_url=yes}} | title=Allmusic - Billboard Albums - Sparks| publisher=Billboard| accessdate=2008-12-04}}</ref>\n\nThe single \"[[I Predict]]\" became Sparks' first entry on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] reaching #60 in May 1982.<ref name=allmusic/> This was the first time since the release of \"Wonder Girl\" in 1971 that Sparks had enjoyed moderate success on the US single charts. An extended remix of \"I Predict\" was released as a club promo while the 7\" single was backed with the album track \"Moustache\". The video for \"I Predict\" was directed by Douglas Brian Martin, cinematography by [[Frederick Elmes]].<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=song|id=t2361068|pure_url=yes}}| title=allmusic - I Predict - Sparks| publisher=\u00a9 2009 Macrovision Corporation. All Rights Reserved. | accessdate=2009-09-21}}</ref>\n\n\"Angst In My Pants\" and \"Eaten by the Monster of Love\" were both used in the movie ''[[Valley Girl (1983 film)|Valley Girl]]'', a romantic comedy released in 1983. \"Eaten by the Monster of Love\" was also featured in the 2009 horror movie [[Cabin Fever 2: Spring Fever|Cabin Fever 2]].  It was also featured the sixth season episode of [[Gilmore Girls]]-The Real [[Paul Anka]].\n\n\"Mickey Mouse,\" while not charting, was performed by the band as they appeared as musical guests on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', hosted by [[Danny DeVito]].  This episode aired on NBC May 15, 1982.  The song was prefaced by a monologue from Ron Mael, in a deadpan style, describing the characteristics of the common mouse leading up to the introduction of the song title.  The band also performed a second cut from the album: \"[[I Predict]].\"\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{track listing\n| all_writing     = Ron Mael and Russell Mael\n| headline        = Side one\n| title1          = Angst in My Pants\n| length1         = 3:25\n| title2          = [[I Predict]]\n| length2         = 2:50\n| title3          = Sextown U.S.A.\n| length3         = 2:56\n| title4          = Sherlock Holmes\n| length4         = 3:34\n| title5          = Nicotina\n| length5         = 3:26\n| title6          = Mickey Mouse\n| length6         = 3:16\n}}\n{{track listing\n| headline        = Side two\n| title7          = Moustache\n| length7         = 3:28\n| title8          = Instant Weight Loss\n| length8         = 3:27\n| title9          = Tarzan and Jane\n| length9         = 3:18\n| title10         = The Decline and Fall of Me\n| length10        = 2:53\n| title11         = Eaten by the Monster of Love\n| length11        = 2:58\n}}\n\n{{track listing\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline        = Imperial Records (Japan) bonus tracks (2009)\n| title12         = Angst in My Pants \n| note12=Radio Promo Ad\n| length12        = 1:03\n| title13         = Kidnap \n| note13=Unreleased Demo\n| length13        = 3:11\n| title14         = A Trying Day \n| note14=Unreleased Demo\n| length14        = 3:21\n| title15         = Dancing Is Dangerous (I Ought to Know) \n| note15=Unreleased Demo\n| length15        = 3:27\n}}\n{{track listing\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline        = Repertoire Records bonus tracks (2013)\n| title12         = Modesty Plays \n| note12=Short Version\n| length12        = 3:07\n| title13         = I Predict \n| note13=Club Mix\n|