y 16, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6GfU5tHba?url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/news/a481826/vin-diesel-fast--furious-7-heading-to-tokyo-middle-east.html |archivedate=May 16, 2013 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Sequel6\">{{cite news|first=Justin |last=Kroll |url=https://variety.com/2013/scene/vpage/vin-diesel-promises-l-a-setting-for-fast-furious-7-1200486389/ |title=Vin Diesel Promises L.A. Setting for 'Fast & Furious 7' |publisher=[[PMC (company)|PMC]] |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=May 22, 2013 |accessdate=May 22, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6GoYdK1yG?url=http://variety.com/2013/scene/vpage/vin-diesel-promises-l-a-setting-for-fast-furious-7-1200486389/ |archivedate=May 22, 2013 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"SequelDec20\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/vin-diesel-seventh-fast-furious-movie-275800 |title=Vin Diesel Confirms Seventh 'Fast and Furious' Movie in the Works |first=Borys |last=Kit |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=December 20, 2011 |accessdate=December 21, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/645RVkP2m?url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/vin-diesel-seventh-fast-furious-movie-275800 |archivedate=December 21, 2011 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"SequelFeb1512\">{{cite web |first=Terri |last=Schwartz |url=http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2012/02/15/dwayne-johnson-fast-six-fast-seven/ |title=Dwayne Johnson Says 'Fast Six' Begins In May, Won't Shoot Back-To-Back For 'Fast Seven' |publisher=Viacom |work=MTV |date=February 15, 2012 |accessdate=February 15, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/65UvgwuWh?url=http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2012/02/15/dwayne-johnson-fast-six-fast-seven/ |archivedate=February 16, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"SequelLaTimes\">{{cite news|last1=Horn |first1=John |last2=Fritz |first2=Ben |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/movies/2011/10/fast-and-furious-6-and-7-speeding-into-production-together.html |title='Fast and Furious' 6 and 7 may speed into production together |publisher=Tribune Company |work=Los Angeles Times |date=October 21, 2011 |accessdate=October 21, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/62bz8XNyF?url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/movies/2011/10/fast-and-furious-6-and-7-speeding-into-production-together.html |archivedate=October 21, 2011 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Indefinite\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/paul-walker-dead-fast-furious-2889701 |title=Fast and Furious 7 production 'shut down indefinitely' following Paul Walker's death |work=[[Daily Mirror]] |publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]] |date=December 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/furious_7/|title=''Furious 7'' (2015) |publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=March 2, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n; Documents\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.thevideographyblog.com/universal-pictures-furious-7-starring-vin-diesel-paul-walker-dwayne-johnson/ | author=[[Universal Pictures]] | via = The Videography Blog | title=Universal Pictures \u2018Furious 7\u2019 Starring Vin Diesel, Paul Walker, & Dwayne Johnson In Theaters April 3, 2015 | accessdate= June 2, 2015 |ref={{SfnRef|Production|2015}}}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.furious7.com}}\n* {{IMDb title|2820852|Furious 7}}\n* {{Amg title|580414|Furious 7}}\n\n{{The Fast and the Furious}}\n{{James Wan}}\n{{Saturn Award for Best Action or Adventure Film}}\n{{Teen Choice Award Choice Movie Action}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:2010s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s chase films]]\n[[Category:2010s heist films]]\n[[Category:2010s road movies]]\n[[Category:2010s sequel films]]\n[[Category:2015 3D films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American 3D films]]\n[[Category:American action thriller films]]\n[[Category:American chase films]]\n[[Category:American heist films]]\n[[Category:American road movies]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:Fast & Furious]]\n[[Category:Films about amnesia]]\n[[Category:Films about automobiles]]\n[[Category:American films about revenge]]\n[[Category:Films about terrorism]]\n[[Category:Films directed by James Wan]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Neal H. Moritz]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Brian Tyler]]\n[[Category:Films set in Azerbaijan]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films set in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Films set in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2014]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Abu Dhabi]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Colorado]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Films shot in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:IMAX films]]\n[[Category:Media Rights Capital films]]\n[[Category:One Race Films films]]\n[[Category:Original Film films]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Chris Morgan]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2015 film by James Wan}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Furious 7\n| image          = Furious 7 poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[James Wan]]\n| producer       = {{Plain list|\n* [[Neal H. Moritz]]\n* [[Vin Diesel]]\n* Michael Fottrell\n}}\n| writer         = [[Chris Morgan (writer)|Chris Morgan]]\n| based on       = {{Based on|[[List of The Fast and the Furious characters|Characters]]|[[Gary Scott Thompson]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plain list|\n* Vin Diesel\n* [[Paul Walker]]\n* [[Dwayne Johnson]]\n* [[Michelle Rodriguez]]\n* [[Tyrese Gibson]]\n* [[Ludacris|Chris \"Ludacris\" Bridges]]\n* [[Jordana Brewster]]\n* [[Djimon Hounsou]]\n* [[Kurt Russell]]\n* [[Jason Statham]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Brian Tyler]]\n| cinematography = {{Plain list|\n* [[Stephen F. Windon]]\n* Marc Spicer\n}}\n| editing        = {{Plain list|\n* [[Christian Wagner]]\n* Dylan Highsmith\n* Kirk Morri\n* Leigh Folsom Boyd\n}}\n| studio         = {{Plain list |\n* [[Original Film]]\n* [[One Race Films]]\n* [[Media Rights Capital|MRC]] \n* [[China Film Group Corporation|China Film]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2015|4|1|[[TCL Chinese Theatre]]|2015|4|3|United States}}\n| runtime        = 140 minutes<ref>{{cite web|title=Event Cinemas - Fast and Furious 7|url=http://www.eventcinemas.com.au/movie/Furious-7|publisher=[[Event Cinemas]]|accessdate=March 18, 2015}}</ref>\n| country        = United States<ref>{{cite news | title = Furious 7 | work = [[The New York Times]] | url = https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/468250/Furious-7/overview | first=A. O. | last=Scott}}</ref>\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $190 million<ref name=BOM/><ref name=profit/>\n| gross          = $1.516 billion<!-- Please update publication date and access date when changing this figure. Round to the nearest million. --><ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=fast7.htm|title=Furious 7 (2015)|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|date=July 14, 2015|accessdate=January 28, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Furious 7''''' (titled onscreen as '''''Fast & Furious 7''''') is a 2015 American [[action film]] directed by [[James Wan]] and written by [[Chris Morgan (writer)|Chris Morgan]]. A sequel to 2013's ''[[Fast & Furious 6]]'', it is the seventh installment in the ''[[Fast & Furious]]'' franchise and stars [[Vin Diesel]], [[Paul Walker]], [[Dwayne Johnson]], [[Michelle Rodriguez]], [[Tyrese Gibson]], [[Ludacris|Chris \"Ludacris\" Bridges]], [[Jordana Brewster]], [[Djimon Hounsou]], [[Kurt Russell]] and [[Jason Statham]]. ''Furious 7'' follows [[Dominic Toretto]] (Diesel), [[Brian O'Conner]] (Walker), and the rest of their team, who have returned to the [[United States]] to live normal lives after securing amnesty for their past crimes in ''Fast & Furious 6'', until Deckard Shaw (Statham), a rogue special forces assassin seeking to avenge his comatose younger brother Owen Shaw, puts the team in danger once again.\n\nWith the previous three installments set between ''[[2 Fast 2 Furious]]'' (2003) and ''[[The Fast and the Furious: Tokyo Drift]]'' (2006), ''Furious 7'' is the first installment in the franchise to take place after ''Tokyo Drift''. The film also marks the final film appearance of Walker, who died in a [[single-vehicle crash]] on November 30, 2013, with filming only half-completed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fast and Furious star Paul Walker killed in car crash|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/dec/01/paul-walker-dies-car-crash|work=Guardian|first=Catherine|last=Shoard|date=1 December 2013}}</ref> Following Walker's death, filming was delayed for script rewrites and his brothers, Caleb and [[Cody Walker (actor)|Cody]], were used as stand-ins to complete his remaining scenes.<ref name=\"Brothers\">{{cite news|title=Paul Walker's Surprising Replacement in Fast & Furious 7|url=http://time.com/64024/paul-walker-replacement-fast-furious-7/|accessdate=25 May 2015|work=[[Time.com]]|publisher=Nolan Feeney|date=April 15, 2014}}</ref> These script rewrites completed the story arc for Walker's character, which was subsequently retired.\n\nPlans for a seventh installment were first announced in February 2012 when Johnson stated that production on the film would begin after the completion of ''Fast & Furious 6''. In April 2013, Wan, predominantly known for horror films, was announced to direct the film in place of [[Justin Lin]], who left the franchise after directing the previous four installments. Casting began in the same month with the returns of Diesel and Walker and an initial release date was set. [[Principal photography]] began in [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], in September 2013, resumed in April 2014 and ended in July 2014, with other filming locations including [[Los Angeles]], [[Colorado]], [[Abu Dhabi]] and [[Tokyo]].\n\n''Furious 7'' premiered in Los Angeles on April 1, 2015 and was theatrically released in the United States on April 3, 2015, playing in [[3D film|3D]], [[IMAX 3D]], and [[4DX]] internationally. Upon release, the film became a critical and blockbuster success, with praise being aimed at the film's action sequences and its emotional tribute to Walker. The film grossed $397.6 million worldwide during its opening weekend, which is the [[List of highest-grossing openings for films|tenth highest-grossing opening of all time]]. The film has grossed over $1.5 billion worldwide, making it the highest-grossing film of the franchise after just twelve days, the third highest-grossing [[2015 in film|film of 2015]]<ref>{{cite web|title = 5 Success Lessons Learned From 'Fast and Furious' Franchise|url = http://www.empirehive.com/success-lessons-learned-from-fast-and-furious/|website = EmpireHive|accessdate = 2015-12-01}}</ref> and the [[List of highest-grossing films|ninth highest-grossing film of all time]].\n\nA sequel, ''[[The Fate of the Furious]]'', was released on April 14, 2017.\n\n== Plot ==\n<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, plot summaries for feature-length films should be between 400 and 700 words. -->\nAfter defeating Owen Shaw and his crew and securing amnesty for their past crimes,{{refn|group=N|As depicted in the 2013 film ''[[Fast & Furious 6]]''.}} [[Dominic Toretto|Dominic \"Dom\" Toretto]], [[Brian O'Conner]], and the rest of their team have returned to the United States to live normal lives again. Brian begins to accustom himself to life as a father, while Dom tries to help Letty Ortiz regain her memory. Meanwhile, Owen's older brother, Deckard Shaw, breaks into the secure hospital that the comatose Owen is being held in and swears vengeance against Dom and his team, before breaking into Luke Hobbs' [[Diplomatic Security Service]] (DSS) office to extract profiles of Dom's crew. After revealing his identity, Shaw engages Hobbs in a fight, and escapes when he detonates a bomb that severely injures Hobbs. Dom later learns from his sister Mia that she is pregnant again and convinces her to tell Brian. However, a [[letter bomb]] sent from [[Tokyo]], explodes and destroys the Toretto house just seconds after Han, a member of Dom's team, is apparently killed by Shaw in Tokyo.{{refn|group=N|As depicted in the 2006 film ''[[The Fast and the Furious: Tokyo Drift]]'' and ''Fast & Furious 6''.}} Dom visits Hobbs in a hospital, where he learns that Shaw is a rogue special forces assassin seeking to avenge his brother. Dom travels to Tokyo to claim Han's body, and acquires personal items found at Han's crash site from Han's friend, Sean Boswell.\n\nDuring Han's funeral in [[Los Angeles]], Dom notices a car observing them, and after a chase, confronts its driver, who is revealed to be Shaw. Shaw flees when a covert ops team arrives and opens fire, led by [[List of The Fast and the Furious characters#Mr. Nobody|Mr. Nobody]]. Nobody says that he will assist Dom in stopping Shaw if he helps him obtain God's Eye, a computer program that uses digital devices to track down a person, and save its creator, a hacker named Ramsey, from a mercenary named Mose Jakande. Dom, Brian, Letty, Roman Pearce, and Tej Parker then [[airdrop]] their cars over the [[Caucasus Mountains]] in Azerbaijan, ambush Jakande's convoy, and rescue Ramsey. The team then heads to [[Abu Dhabi]], where a billionaire has acquired the flash drive containing God's Eye, and manages to steal it from the owner. With God's Eye near [[repeater|telecommunications repeaters]], the team tracks down Shaw, who is waiting at a remote factory. Dom, Brian, Nobody and his team attempt to capture Shaw, but are ambushed by Jakande and his men, and are forced to flee while Jakande obtains God's Eye. At his own request, the injured Nobody is left behind to be evacuated by helicopter while Brian and Dom continue without him. To reduce their disadvantage, the crew returns to Los Angeles to fight Shaw, Jakande and his men. Meanwhile, Brian promises Mia that once they deal with Shaw, he will retire and fully dedicate himself to their family.\n\nWhile Jakande pursues Brian and the rest of the team with a [[stealth helicopter]] and an [[unmanned combat aerial vehicle|aerial drone]], Ramsey attempts to hack into God's Eye. Hobbs, seeing the team in trouble, leaves the hospital and destroys the drone with an ambulance. Brian engages Jakande's henchman Kiet and throws him down an elevator shaft before hijacking a signal repeater tower, allowing Ramsey to regain control of God's Eye and shut it down. Dom and Shaw engage in a one-on-one brawl on top of a public parking garage, before Jakande intervenes and attacks them both. Shaw is defeated when part of the parking garage collapses beneath him. Dom then launches his vehicle at Jakande's helicopter, tossing Shaw's bag of grenades onto its skids, though his car crash-lands. Hobbs then shoots the bag of grenades from ground level, destroying the helicopter and killing Jakande. Dom is pulled from the wreckage of his car, believed to be dead. As Letty cradles Dom's body in her arms, she reveals that she has regained her memories, and that she remembers their wedding. Dom regains consciousness soon after, remarking, \"It's about time\".\n\nShaw is taken into custody by Hobbs and locked away in a secret, high-security prison. At a beach, Brian and Mia play with their son while Dom, Letty, Roman, Tej, and Ramsey observe, acknowledging that Brian is better off retired with his family. As Dom silently leaves, Ramsey asks if he intends to say goodbye. Dom says, \"It's never goodbye.\" He drives away, but Brian catches up with him at a crossroad. \n\nAs Dom remembers the times that he had with Brian, they bid each other farewell and drive off in separate directions.\n\n==Cast==\n[[File:PaulWalkerEdit-1.jpg|175px|right|thumb|''Furious 7'' marked the final film performance of [[Paul Walker]], who died in a car accident on November 30, 2013. The film was dedicated to his memory.]]\n{{details|topic=the characters|List of Fast & Furious characters}}\n<!-- list as billed in film per [[WP:CASTLIST]], opening credits -->\n* [[Vin Diesel]] as [[Dominic Toretto]], a former criminal and professional street racer who has retired and settled down with his wife, Letty.\n* [[Paul Walker]] as [[Brian O'Conner]], a former [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] agent turned criminal and professional street racer who has retired and settled down with his partner, Mia, and their son, Jack. This was Walker's last role in a film before his death on November 30, 2013.\n** Caleb and [[Cody Walker (actor)|Cody Walker]], Paul's younger brothers, were used among others as stand-ins <!-- Credited as Stand-ins in closing credits --> to complete his remaining scenes following their brother's death.<ref name=\"Brothers\"/>\n* [[Dwayne Johnson]] as [[Luke Hobbs]], a [[Diplomatic Security Service|DSS]] agent who allied with Dom and his team after their outings in [[Rio de Janeiro]] and [[Europe]]. Johnson initially said that if [[Universal Studios|Universal Pictures]] pursued the accelerated development of a seventh film beginning in the summer, he would be unable to participate due to scheduling conflicts with filming on ''[[Hercules (2014 film)|Hercules]]''.<ref name=\"Sequel3\"/> However, as production for ''Furious 7'' would commence in September, Johnson confirmed his return for, as ''Hercules'' would complete production in time to enable him to film a significant part.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=TheRock|author=Dwayne Johnson|number=365921807393505280|date=9 August 2013|title=She rocks my Championship belt better than me! My fam @UFC Champ @RondaRousey joins me in FAST &amp; FURIOUS 7! #BringIt}}</ref>\n* [[Michelle Rodriguez]] as [[Letty Ortiz]], Dom's wife and a professional street racer, who was revealed to have suffered from amnesia after being presumed dead in ''[[Fast & Furious (2009 film)|Fast & Furious]]''.\n* [[Tyrese Gibson]] as [[Roman Pearce]], a former criminal and childhood friend of Brian from [[Barstow, California|Barstow]], and a member of Dom's team.\n* [[Ludacris|Chris \"Ludacris\" Bridges]] as [[Tej Parker]], a mechanic from [[Miami]] and a member of Dom's team.\n* [[Jordana Brewster]] as [[Mia Toretto]], Dom's younger sister and a former member of his team who has settled down with her partner, Brian, and their son, Jack.\n* [[Djimon Hounsou]] as Mose Jakande, a [[Nigerian]] born mercenary and terrorist who leads a private military company that allies with Shaw and uses the God's Eye to track its creator and use her to track down his enemies.{{sfn|Production|2015}}\n* [[Tony Jaa]] as Kiet, a member of Jakande's team who possesses great agility, athleticism and fighting prowess. Thai martial arts actor Jaa was confirmed to have joined the cast in August 2013, making his Hollywood debut.<ref name=\"Hollywood Reporter\">{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/fast-furious-7-tony-jaa-598052 |title=Asian Star Tony Jaa Joins 'Fast and Furious 7' (Exclusive) |author=Kit, Borys |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=August 23, 2013 |accessdate=August 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.ign.com/articles/2013/08/24/ong-baks-tony-jaa-joins-fast-and-furious-7|title=''Ong Bak''{{'}}s Tony Jaa Joins ''Fast and Furious 7''|last=Collura|first=Scott|work=IGN.com|date=August 23, 2013 |accessdate=August 24, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Ronda Rousey]] as Kara, the Head of Security for an [[Abu Dhabi]] billionaire. Rousey's involvement was confirmed in August 2013. Having committed to ''[[The Expendables 3]]'' at the same time (along with Russell, who later pulled out, and Statham), Rousey was forced to shoot both films back-to-back in order to allow herself 45 days to focus on training for her [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]] championship rematch against [[Miesha Tate]]. Her participation in the film was similar to that of [[Gina Carano]] making the transition from mixed martial arts fighting to acting, following Carano's involvement in ''[[Fast & Furious 6]]''.<ref name=\"CastRousey\"/>\n* [[Nathalie Emmanuel]] as [[List of Fast & Furious characters#Ramsey|Ramsey]], a British computer [[Hacktivism|hacktivist]] and the creator of the God's Eye, who allies with Dom and his team after being saved from Jakande and helps them to regain control of her program.{{sfn|Production|2015}}\n<!-- \"With\" credit in opening credits -->\n* [[Kurt Russell]] as [[List of Fast & Furious characters#Mr. Nobody|Mr. Nobody]], the leader of a covert ops team who agrees to help Dom stop Shaw if he can help him prevent Jakande from obtaining a computer program called the God's Eye.\n<!--- \"and\" credit in opening credits -->\n* [[Jason Statham]] as Deckard Shaw, a rogue special forces assassin seeking to avenge his comatose younger brother after his hospitalization at the hands of Dom and his team in [[Spain]].<!-- listed two at a time in opening credits -->\n* [[Lucas Black]] as [[Sean Boswell]], an American street racer who lives in [[Tokyo]] whom Dom meets when he travels to Tokyo to claim the body of Han, a mutual friend of theirs killed by Shaw. In September, it was confirmed that Black had signed on to reprise his role as Boswell for ''Furious 7'' and two more installments.<ref name=\"CinemaBlend\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/new/Lucas-Black-Signs-Fast-Furious-7-8-9-39448.html |title=Lucas Black Signs On For Fast & Furious 7, 8 And 9 |author=Eisenberg, Eric |publisher=Cinema Blend |date=September 16, 2013 |accessdate=September 17, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Deadline\">{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/09/lucas-back-is-back-behind-the-wheel-for-fast-furious-7-and-beyond/|title=Lucas Black Is Back Behind The Wheel For 'Fast & Furious 7' And Beyond|last=Fleming|first=Mike|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=September 16, 2013|accessdate=September 17, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Elsa Pataky]] as [[Elena Neves]], a DSS agent and former Rio police officer who moved to the United States to become Hobbs' new partner at the DSS.\n* [[Noel Gugliemi]] as [[Hector]], a street race organizer, reprising his role from the [[The Fast and the Furious (2001 film)|first film]].\n* [[John Brotherton]] as Sheppard, Mr. Nobody's right-hand man.{{sfn|Production|2015}}<ref>{{cite news|last1=Riley|first1=Jenelle|title=James Wan on Continuing 'Furious 7\u2032 After Death of Paul Walker|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/furious-7-james-wan-director-paul-walker-1201447340/|accessdate=20 April 2015|work=Variety|date=March 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Murphy|first1=Mekado|last2=Soto|first2=Kaly|title='Furious 7' (With Movie Trailer): James Wan Discusses Paul Walker and Narrates a Scene|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/01/movies/furious-7-with-movie-trailer-james-wan-discusses-paul-walker-and-narrates-a-scene.html?_r=0|accessdate=20 April 2015|newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 1, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/adambvary/the-daunting-task-of-making-furious-7-without-paul-walker#.awOz7Pb9P|title=The Daunting Task Of Making \"Furious 7\" Without Paul Walker|author=Vary, Adam B.|date=April 2, 2015|website=Buzzfeed|access-date=April 20, 2015}}</ref><!-- others only listed as closing credits -->\n* [[Ali Fazal]] plays Safar, a friend of Ramsey to whom she sent the God's Eye for safekeeping. Fazal described his role as a [[cameo appearance|cameo]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://gulfnews.com/life-style/celebrity/desi-news/bollywood/ali-fazal-on-his-furious-7-cameo-1.1483016 | title=Ali Fazal on his 'Furious 7' cameo | work=gulfnews.com | author=Manjusha Radhakrishnan}}</ref>\n* [[Luke Evans]] briefly reprises his role from the previous film as [[Owen Shaw]], the comatose younger brother of the film's primary antagonist.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.motorauthority.com/news/1029886_furious-7-will-see-the-return-of-race-wars|title='Furious 7' Will See The Return Of Race Wars!|author=Vijayenthiran, Viknesh|date=October 31, 2014|website=Motor Authority|access-date=March 31, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Sung Kang]] as [[List of Fast & Furious characters#Han|Han]], a member in Dominic's crew, appearing in archive footage.\n* [[Gal Gadot]] as [[List of Fast & Furious characters#Gisele|Gisele]], a member in Dominic's crew, appearing in archive footage.\n* Australian rapper [[Iggy Azalea]] makes a cameo appearance as a Race Wars fan and a female racer; she contributed to the soundtrack.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rosen|first1=Christopher|title=Everything Iggy Azalea Says In 'Furious 7'|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/04/01/iggy-azalea-furious-7_n_6984674.html|accessdate=2 April 2015|work=Huffington Post|date=April 1, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/6516987/romeo-santos-furious-7-acting-debut|title=Romeo Santos Shares Which 'Furious 7' Co-Star Eased His Acting Debut Jitters|author=Romero, Angie|date=March 31, 2015|website=Billboard|access-date=April 7, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6523987/iggy-azalea-furious-7-line|title=Here's Iggy Azalea's Fast, Less-Than-Furious Line of Dialogue in 'Furious 7'|website=Billboard.com|accessdate=August 30, 2017}}</ref> American singer-rapper [[T-Pain]] appears as himself as he DJs a party in Abu Dhabi.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2015/04/t-pain-on-aaliyah-furious-7-and-fka-twigs.html |title=T-Pain on What Happened to His Aaliyah Collaboration, Furious 7, and FKA Twigs's Engagement to Robert Pattinson [Updated] |author=Lockett, Dee |date=August 1, 2015 |website=Vulture |publisher= New York Media LLC |access-date=November 1, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/2015/3/20/8262069/fast-furious-7-movie-review|title='Furious 7' may the greatest movie I've ever seen|first=Bill|last=Hanstock|date=March 20, 2015|website=SBNation.com|accessdate=August 30, 2017}}</ref> [[Klement Tinaj]] cameos as a Race Wars Racer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gazetadielli.com/actor-and-martial-artist-klement-tinaj-cast-in-fast-furious-7/ |title=Actor and Martial Artist Klement Tinaj Cast in \"Fast & Furious 7\" [Updated] |author=Babamusta, Ermira |date=April 3, 2015 |website=Dielli Online |accessdate=April 3, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Bow Wow (rapper)|Bow Wow]] and [[Nathalie Kelley]] appear in archive footage from ''[[The Fast and the Furious: Tokyo Drift]]'' as Twinkie and Neela, respectively.\n* [[Tego Calder\u00f3n]] and [[Don Omar]] and Christopher Anderson appear as Tego Leo and Rico Santos and Johnny PS, respectively, in archive footage from ''[[Fast Five]]''.\n* John Cenatiempo appears as Korpi and Sophia Jensen as Kenpi reprising their roles from ''[[2 Fast 2 Furious]]'', now serving as one of Mose Jakande's henchmen.\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nOn October 21, 2011, the ''Los Angeles Times'' reported that [[Universal Pictures|Universal Studios]] was considering filming two sequels\u2014''[[Fast & Furious 6|Fast Six]]'' and ''Fast Seven''\u2014[[Back to back film production|back-to-back]] with a single storyline running through both films. Both would be written by [[Chris Morgan (writer)|Chris Morgan]] and directed by [[Justin Lin]], who had been the franchise's writer and director, respectively, since ''[[The Fast and the Furious: Tokyo Drift]]'' (2006).<ref name=\"SequelLaTimes\"/> On December 20, 2011, following the release of ''[[Fast Five]]'', [[Vin Diesel]] stated that ''Fast Six'' would be split into two parts, with writing for the two films occurring simultaneously. On the decision, Diesel said:<ref name=\"SequelDec20\"/>\n\n<blockquote>We have to pay off this story, we have to service all of these character relationships, and when we started mapping all that out it just went beyond 110 pages&nbsp; ... &nbsp;The studio said, 'You can't fit all that story in one damn movie!'<ref name=\"SequelDec20\"/></blockquote>\n\nHowever, in an interview on February 15, 2012, [[Dwayne Johnson]] stated that the two intended sequels would no longer be filmed simultaneously because of weather issues in filming locations, and that production on ''Fast Seven'' would only begin after the completion of ''Fast Six''.<ref name=\"SequelFeb1512\"/>\n\nIn April 2013, during post-production of the retitled ''Fast & Furious 6'', Lin announced that he would not return to direct a seventh film, as the studio wanted to produce the film on an accelerated schedule for release in summer 2014. This would have required Lin to begin pre-production on the sequel while performing post-production on ''Fast & Furious 6'', which he considered would affect the quality of the final product. Despite the usual two-year gap between the previous installments, Universal chose to pursue a sequel quicker due to having fewer reliable franchises than its competitor studios.<ref name=\"Sequel1\"/> However, subsequent interviews with Lin have suggested that the sixth film was always intended to be the final installment under his direction.<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview: Fast & Furious 6 Director Justin Lin|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=104306|work=Comingsoon.net|accessdate=October 29, 2013|date=May 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2013, Australian director [[James Wan]], predominantly known for [[horror film]]s, was announced as the sequel's director, with [[Neal H. Moritz]] and Michael Fottrell returning to produce and Morgan returning to write the script, his fifth in the franchise. On April 16, 2013, Diesel announced that the sequel would be released on July 11, 2014.<ref name=\"Sequel4\"/> In May 2013, Diesel said that the sequel would feature [[Los Angeles]], [[Tokyo]], and the [[Middle East]] as locations.<ref name=\"Sequel5\"/><ref name=\"Sequel6\"/>\n\n===Filming===\nPrincipal photography began in early September 2013 in [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], with a casting call issued.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.accessatlanta.com/weblogs/buzz/2013/aug/21/fast-and-furious-7-about-start-filming/ |title=\"Fast and Furious 7\" about to start filming in Atlanta; casting call |author=Brett, Jennifer |publisher=Access Atlanta |date=August 21, 2013 |accessdate=August 26, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130825063720/http://www.accessatlanta.com/weblogs/buzz/2013/aug/21/fast-and-furious-7-about-start-filming/ |archivedate=August 25, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Seven ... Has begun ...|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=10151951370948313|first=Vin|last=Diesel |publisher=[[Facebook]] |date=September 13, 2013 |accessdate=November 8, 2013}}</ref> [[Abu Dhabi]] was also a filming location;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://media.twofour54.com/en/news/news/filming-of-universal-pictures-fast-furious-7-in-abu-dhabi-now-confirmed-for-april.html |title=Filming of Universal Pictures' Fast & Furious 7 in Abu Dhabi Now Confirmed for April |publisher=[[twofour54|twofour54 Abu Dhabi]] |date=March 12, 2014 |accessdate=March 12, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140312224534/http://media.twofour54.com/en/news/news/filming-of-universal-pictures-fast-furious-7-in-abu-dhabi-now-confirmed-for-april.html |archive-date=March 12, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> the production crew chose it over [[Dubai]], as they would benefit from the Emirate's 30% rebate scheme.<ref name=\"The National\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/film/fast-furious-7-will-be-filmed-in-uae-confirms-twofour54 |title=Fast & Furious 7 will be filmed in UAE confirms twofour54 |author=Olson, Marie-Louise |newspaper=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]] |date=August 13, 2013 |accessdate=August 26, 2013}}</ref> [[Pikes Peak Highway]] in [[Colorado]] was closed in September to film some driving sequences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gazette.com/pikes-peak-could-be-star-of-next-fast-and-furious-installment/article/1504957|title=Pikes Peak could be star of next 'Fast and Furious' installment|last=Handy|first=Ryan|work=The Gazette|date=August 16, 2013|accessdate=August 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn September 16, the production filmed with [[Paul Walker]] and the Kimsey twins, playing his son, Jack,<ref>{{cite web |title=Twins \u2013 Fast Furious 7 |url=http://millielewiscolumbia.com/twins-fast-furious-7/ |publisher=Millie Lewis Columbia |date=September 25, 2013 |accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref> in front of an Atlanta elementary school.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"Fast & Furious 7\" starts filming in Atlanta |url=http://www.accessatlanta.com/weblogs/buzz/2013/sep/16/fast-furious-7-starts-filming-atlanta |publisher=Access Atlanta |date=September 16, 2013 |accessdate=April 23, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921231558/http://www.accessatlanta.com/weblogs/buzz/2013/sep/16/fast-furious-7-starts-filming-atlanta |archivedate=September 21, 2013 }}</ref> Han's funeral scene was filmed at [[Oakland Cemetery (Atlanta)|Oakland Cemetery]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.myajc.com/weblogs/buzz/2013/sep/18/fast-furious-7-oakland-cemetery-today/ |title=\"Fast & Furious 7\" filming in Atlanta today |author=Brett, Jennifer |newspaper=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution |date=September 18, 2013 |accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref> with extras needed for the scene being \"hot, hip and trendy cool types of all ethnicities between the ages of 18 and 45\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.11alive.com/story/entertainment/2014/03/05/1947620/ |title='Fast & Furious 7' looking for extras |author=Atlanta Business Chronicle |publisher=NBC 11 Alive |date=September 17, 2013 |accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref> On the evening of September 19, [[Lucas Black]] joined the production<ref>{{cite tweet|user=TheLucasBlack|author=Lucas Black|number=380509370900967425|date=19 September 2013|title=Excited to go on set tomorrow for #Fast7. #HanIsFamily}}</ref> for his sole scene with Diesel, in an Atlanta parking garage. Separate scenes with Walker also shot in the same location on the same night,<ref>{{cite web|title=Location photo|url=http://fandimefilmu.cz/gal/Filmy/Rychle_a_zbesile_7/Rychle_a_zbesile_116.jpg |date=September 19, 2013 |accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref> including one half of a phone conversation between his character and [[Jordana Brewster]]'s. The day after, Diesel posted a picture from the night shoot with Black on his [[Facebook]] page.<ref>{{cite web |title=Vin Diesel's facebook post|url=https://www.facebook.com/VinDiesel/photos/pb.89562268312.-2207520000.1385236552./10151969539933313/?type=3&permPage=1 |author=Diesel, Vin |publisher=Facebook |date=September 20, 2013 |accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn October 24, over a month into the film's production, Johnson tweeted he had started shooting for the film after wrapping up on ''[[Hercules (2014 film)|Hercules]]''.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=TheRock|author=Dwayne Johnson|number=393424557048344577|date=24 October 2013|title=Intense 6 months of HERCULES to now Hobbs (Fast &amp; Furious). Shooting starts now. #50ShadesOfAttitude}}</ref> Five days later, Diesel posted the first photo of Johnson on the set, in the hospital scene.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/VinDiesel/photos/a.101465923312.101581.89562268312/10152054670848313/?type=1&permPage=1 |title=When brother Dwayne steps into the Hobbs role ... you can't tell where he ends, or the character begins. Our third consecutive chapter in the saga, and the short hand we've established makes the film that much better each time. P.s. Proud of Our whole Fast team. |author=Diesel, Vin |publisher=Facebook |date=October 29, 2013 |accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn November 30, 2013, while on a break for the Thanksgiving holiday, Walker, who portrayed Brian O'Conner, died in a [[single-vehicle accident]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-25173331|title=Fast & Furious actor Paul Walker dies in California car crash|author=Moh, Catharina|publisher=BBC|date=December 1, 2013|accessdate=December 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/486238/paul-walker-s-fatal-car-crash-what-we-know-about-the-accident|title=News/Paul Walker's Fatal Car Crash: What We Know About the Accident|author=Ossad, Jordana|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=December 1, 2013|accessdate=December 2, 2013}}</ref> The next day, Universal announced that production would continue after a delay that would allow the filmmakers to rework the film.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/486246/fast-and-furious-7-delayed-but-won-t-be-scrapped-following-paul-walker-s-death-report |title=News/''Fast and Furious 7'' \"Delayed\" But \"Won't Be Scrapped\" Following Paul Walker's Death: Report |author=Ossad, Jordana |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=December 1, 2013 |accessdate=December 2, 2013}}</ref> On December 4, 2013, Universal put production on hold indefinitely.<ref name=\"Indefinite\"/> Wan later confirmed that the film had not been cancelled.<ref>{{cite news|title='Fast & Furious 7' Production Will See The Light Of Day, Says Director James Wan|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/12/07/fast-and-furious-7-production_n_4404582.html|work=Huffington Post | first=Jacobs|last=Matthew|date=December 7, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tmz.com/2013/12/07/fast-and-furious-7-director-james-wan-movie-not-cancelled/ |title='Fast and Furious 7' Director - We WILL Finish Making the Movie |publisher=TMZ.com |date=December 7, 2013 |accessdate=December 15, 2013}}</ref> On December 22, 2013, Diesel announced on his Facebook page that the film would be released on April 10, 2015.<ref name=\"Vin Diesel FB\">{{cite web|title=Vin Diesel - The last scene we filmed together ...|url=https://www.facebook.com/VinDiesel/posts/10152194533203313|last=Diesel|first=Vin|publisher=Facebook|date=December 22, 2013|accessdate=December 23, 2013}}</ref> On February 27, 2014, ''The Hollywood Reporter'' reported that filming would resume on April 1, and that the cast and crew had headed to Atlanta to prepare for about eight more weeks of shooting.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ford |first=Rebecca |url=https://hollywoodreporter.com/news/paul-walker-fast-furious-7-683883 |title='Fast & Furious 7' to Resume Production in April |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=February 27, 2014|accessdate=February 27, 2014}}</ref> Principal photography ended on July 10, 2014.<ref name=\"F&F7\">{{cite news|last1=Yamato|first1=Jen|title='Fast & Furious 7' Wraps Filming, Thanks Fans On Eve Of Original Release Date|url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/07/fast-furious-7-wraps-filming-thank-you-to-fans/|accessdate=July 11, 2014|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=July 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Stunts===\n[[File:Hercules met parachutisten op Ginkelse heide 19 september 2009.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/04/08/us/c-130-hercules-military-plane-anniversary/|title=The 'Furious 7' plane that just won't quit|first=Thom|last=Patterson|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=April 8, 2015|accessdate=April 9, 2015}}</ref> was used in the film to carry the vehicles that would drop from 12,000 feet high, above the [[Sonoran Desert]], making cars plummet at a speed of about 130 to 140 miles per hour.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2015/03/30/how-furious-7-filmmakers-pushed-5-cars-out-a-plane-at-12000-feet/|title=How 'Furious 7' filmmakers pushed 5 cars out of a plane at 12,000 feet|first=Reed|last=Tucker|newspaper=[[New York Post]]|date=March 30, 2015|accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://au.ibtimes.com/furious-7-stunt-coordinators-crew-members-speak-about-air-drop-scene-movie-1429693|title='Furious 7' Stunt Coordinators And Crew Members Speak About The Air Drop Scene In The Movie|first=Sachin|last=Trivedi|newspaper=[[International Business Times]]|date=March 16, 2015|accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref>]]\n\nThe \"air drop\" sequence was conceived by stunt coordinator, Spiro Razatos, who also supervised on the franchise's two previous installments; ''[[Fast Five]]'' and ''[[Fast & Furious 6]]''.<ref name=\"BI\"/><ref name=\"USA\"/> Razatos told ''[[Business Insider]]'' that he wanted to rely more on real stunts rather than [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] because he wanted the whole sequence to \"feel real\" and fulfill audience's expectations.<ref name=\"BI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.in/How-Furious-7-dropped-real-cars-from-planes-in-its-most-ridiculous-stunt-yet/articleshow/46790017.cms|title=How 'Furious 7' dropped real cars from planes in its most ridiculous stunt yet|first=Jason|last=Guerrasio|website=[[Business Insider]]|date=April 3, 2015|accessdate=April 3, 2015}}</ref> The stunt took months of prep-solving problems. Cameras needed to be mounted onto cars in a way that they would not be destroyed when the cars landed, and the crew had to figure out a safe way to get the cars out of the plane. They performed a [[dry run (testing)|dry run]] with a single car falling out of a plane<ref name=\"BI\"/> and did this six times.<ref name=\"USA\"/> Cars were dropped from a [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules]] high above the [[Arizona desert]], but close up shots that show the cars landing on a mountain road were filmed in Colorado.<ref name=\"USA\">{{cite news|url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/04/secrets-behind-the-three-most-amazing-stunts-in-furious-7|title=The secrets behind the three most amazing stunts in 'Furious 7'|first=Hamel|last=Jhavera|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=April 3, 2015|accessdate=April 6, 2015}}</ref> There were two airplanes, flying at a height of 12,000 feet, each dropping two cars apiece.<ref name=\"BI\"/> [[Ballistic Recovery Systems|BRS parachutes]] enabled with GPS were secured to each of the cars before dropping off the C-130 plane. At about 5,000 feet, the parachutes deployed.<ref name=\"USA\"/> Over 10 cameras were used for the sequence. In addition to cameras on the ground, there were cameras remotely operated inside the plane and another three mounted outside each car. Additional cameras were on a helicopter, where Razatos was stationed watching monitors. Three skydivers used in the shoot wore helmet cameras to help shoot the sequence from multiple angles. Sky divers would either jump out before cars or after them.<ref name=\"BI\"/> While all the cars landed on their drop zones, 70% landed perfectly and 30% didn't.<ref name=\"USA\"/> For the close-up scenes which show the actors inside their cars, a giant [[gimbal]] with a 360-degree range of movement were attached to each of the cars and was filmed against a [[Chroma key|green screen]] to reproduce their tumble through the sky.<ref name=\"OCR\">{{cite news|url=http://m.ocregister.com/articles/car-656462-cars-furious.html|title=Reel deal steel|first=Susan|last=Carpenter|newspaper=[[Orange County Register]]|accessdate=April 10, 2015}}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The last part of the scene, which shows the cars hitting the road was shot separately. To get that right, the team set up a pulley system that had cars six to ten feet above the ground. When they were dropped from the cranes, the stuntmen who were sitting in the driver's seats raced their engines at about 35 to 40 miles per hour and slid to the ground at full speed. Those cranes were then later removed from the film with computers.<ref name=\"USA\"/><ref name=\"OCR\"/> Razatos admits that the air drop sequence was \"all real\" and that it would be \"hard to top\".<ref name=\"BI\"/><ref name=\"USA\"/>\n\nThe scene featuring Brian jumping off a bus off a cliff was performed by a stuntman and was all done without any computer graphics.<ref name=\"S2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.in/One-of-the-most-insane-stunts-in-Furious-7-almost-didnt-happen/articleshow/46818645.cms|title=One of the most insane stunts in 'Furious 7' almost didn't happen|first=Jason|last=Guerrasio|website=[[Business Insider]]|date=April 6, 2015|accessdate=April 6, 2015}}</ref> The shooting for this particular sequence along with the scene in which Dom and his team are pursuing to rescue Ramsey almost didn't happen due to the absence of [[tax break]] in Colorado.<ref name=\"S2\"/> The studio originally wanted to shoot the sequence in [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] which provides tax breaks for film productions, and then they'd add woods in the background later in post production to which Razatos denied saying, \"the audience is going to know [it's CGI] and aren't going to feel good about it.\"<ref name=\"S2\"/> Shooting finally took place in Colorado.<ref name=\"S2\"/>\n\nA total of 340 cars were used in the film,<ref name=\"OCR\"/> and more than 230 cars were destroyed in the making of the film, including several black [[Mercedes-Benz]]es, a [[Ford Crown Victoria]], and a [[Mitsubishi Montero]].<ref name=\"WSJ\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/furious-7-what-happened-to-the-wrecked-cars-1427907293|title='Furious 7': What Happened to the Wrecked Cars|first=Steve|last=Knopper|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=April 1, 2015|accessdate=April 10, 2015}}</ref> The film featured the on-screen destruction of a [[Lykan HyperSport]] by [[W Motors]], valued at $3.4 million,<ref name=\"LH\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/fast-furious-franchise-damage-would-cost-514-million-expert-estimates-990021|title='Fast & Furious' Franchise Damage Would Cost $514 Million, Expert Estimates|author=Ashley Lee|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=March 30, 2017|accessdate=March 31, 2017}}</ref> though the actual car destroyed was a less expensive model made for the film rather than one of the seven actual production HyperSports.<ref>[https://www.theverge.com/2015/3/24/8282803/furious-7-car-coordinator-interview A Q&A with Dennis McCarthy, the man behind Furious 7's insane cast of cars]. ''[[The Verge]]'', March 24, 2015.</ref> The mountain-highway chase scene on Colorado's [[Monarch Pass]] proved to be the most damaging sequence with over 40 vehicles being destroyed.<ref name=\"WSJ\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/furious-7-230-cars-were-787486|title='Furious 7': Over 230 Cars Were Destroyed During Film's Shoot|first=Ryan|last=Gajewski|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=April 9, 2015|accessdate=April 10, 2015}}</ref> Only 10 percent of the action sequences in the film were computer-generated, and even then, much of the CGI was employed simply to erase the wires and other contraptions that were used to film real cars and drivers or to add a background.<ref name=\"OCR\"/> It took more than 3,500 [[Man-hour|man-days]] to complete the various stunts of the film.<ref name=\"OCR\"/>\n\n===Redevelopment of Walker's character===\n{{quote box|width=33%|align=right|quote=When I first heard the news, I was shell-shocked like everyone, and it took me days to come to terms with it. And then after that, heartbreaks started sinking in and we realized that Paul [Walker] wasn't going to be around with us anymore moving forward, and it was a really hard one. And finishing the movie was the last thing on my mind at that point. It was more the idea of ... picking up the pieces, going back on set, rallying the team, the cast, and the crew, and as the director, having to put on the brave face and champion and push everyone along. The idea of that was very daunting for me, but it became very apparent to all of us that we needed to finish this movie to honour Paul's legacy and to basically honour his memories ... it was about making this movie for Paul.|source= \u2014[[James Wan]], director of ''Furious 7''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.hindustantimes.com/hollywood/before-paul-walker-died-this-was-the-fast-and-furious-7-climax/article1-1335118.aspx|title=Before Paul Walker died, this was the Fast and Furious 7 climax|work=[[Hindustan Times]]|date=April 8, 2015|accessdate=April 9, 2015}}</ref>}}\n\nIn January 2014, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' reported that Walker's character, Brian O'Conner, would be retired instead of killed, and that new scenes would be developed in order to allow the franchise to continue without him.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://entertainment.time.com/2014/01/06/heres-what-will-happen-to-paul-walkers-character-in-fast-and-furious-7/ |title=Paul Walker's Fast and Furious Fate: How The Movie Will Deal With His Death |last=Stampler|first=Laura |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=January 6, 2014|accessdate=January 13, 2014}}</ref> To recreate Walker's likeness, the filmmakers hired [[Peter Jackson]]'s [[Weta Digital]] visual effects house (which had previously produced the imagery of [[Gollum]] in [[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|''The Lord of the Rings'' franchise]] and Caesar in the [[Planet of the Apes (franchise)|''Planet of the Apes'' franchise]]).<ref name=\"Giardina\">{{cite news|last1=Giardina|first1=Carolyn|title=How 'Furious 7' Brought the Late Paul Walker Back to Life|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/behind-screen/how-furious-7-brought-late-845763|accessdate=6 January 2017|work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=11 December 2015|location=Los Angeles}}</ref> Initially, what Weta could do was severely constrained by the quality of the reference materials available for Walker's physical appearance. In April 2014, it was reported that Walker's brothers Caleb and [[Cody Walker (actor)|Cody]] had been hired as stand-ins.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/04/paul-walker-brothers-fast-furious-7-filming-help/ |title=Paul Walker's Brothers Jumping In To Help Finish 'Fast & Furious 7' Action Scenes |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=April 15, 2014 |accessdate=May 4, 2014}}</ref>  Their cooperation, along with their strong resemblance to their late brother, enabled the filmmakers to accurately model his face without creating it digitally from scratch. The final film showed Walker's face superimposed over the bodies of his brothers or actor John Brotherton in 350 visual effects shots. 260 used a computer-generated face, while 90 repurposed actual footage of Walker's face borrowed from outtakes or older footage.<ref name=\"Giardina\"/>\n\n==Music==\n{{Main|Furious 7: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|Furious 7 (score)}}\nThe [[film score|musical score]] was composed by [[Brian Tyler]], who scored the third, fourth, and fifth installments of the series.<ref name=\"FilmMusicReporter\">{{cite web|title=Brian Tyler to Score 'Fast & Furious 7'|url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2013/10/22/brian-tyler-to-score-fast-furious-7/|work=Film Music Reporter|accessdate=October 23, 2013|date=October 22, 2013}}</ref> \"There's an emotional component to ''Fast & Furious 7'' that is unique\", said Tyler about his experience scoring. \"I think people are really going to be amazed by it.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Niles|first1=Jon|title=[EXCLUSIVE INTERVIEW]: Brian Tyler - Composer For 'The Expendables 3,' 'TMNT,' 'Avengers: Age of Ultron,' & Many More Movies Talks Music To Film, TV & Video Games|url=http://www.musictimes.com/articles/8767/20140814/exclusive-interview-brian-tyler-composer-expendables-3-tmnt-avengers-age.htm|website=Music Times|accessdate=March 16, 2015|date=August 14, 2014}}</ref> A soundtrack album to the film was released by [[Atlantic Records]] on March 17, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gallo|first1=Phil|title='Furious 7' Soundtrack Launches With 7 Singles|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/6472998/furious-7-soundtrack-listing|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=March 16, 2015|date=February 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSongs featured in the film include:\n* \"[[Go Hard or Go Home (song)|Go Hard or Go Home]]\" ([[Wiz Khalifa]] & [[Iggy Azalea]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2015/02/13/new-music-wiz-khalifa-iggy-azalea-go-hard-or-go-home-snippet/|title=New Music: Wiz Khalifa & Iggy Azalea \u2013 'Go Hard or Go Home' [Snippet]|work=Rap-Up}}</ref>\n* \"[[Ride Out]]\" ([[Kid Ink]], [[Tyga]], [[Wale (rapper)|Wale]], [[YG (rapper)|YG]] & [[Rich Homie Quan]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2015/02/12/new-music-kid-ink-tyga-wale-yg-rich-homie-quan-ride-out/|title=New Music: Kid Ink, Tyga, Wale, YG & Rich Homie Quan \u2013 'Ride Out'|work=Rap-Up}}</ref>\n* \"[[See You Again]]\" (Wiz Khalifa and [[Charlie Puth]])\n* \"My Angel\" ([[Prince Royce]])\n* \"Hamdulillah\" ([[Narcy (rapper)|Narcy]] feat. [[Shadia Mansour]])\n* \"[[Get Low (Dillon Francis and DJ Snake song)|Get Low]]\" ([[Dillon Francis]] and [[DJ Snake]])\n* \"[[Ay Vamos]]\" ([[J Balvin]] feat. [[Nicky Jam]] and [[French Montana]])\n* \"[[Tempest (Deftones song)|Tempest]]\" ([[Deftones]])\n* \"Meneo\" ([[Fito Blanko]])\n*\"Payback\" (Juicy J, Kevin Gates, Future and Sage the Gemini)\n\nWiz Khalifa and Charlie Puth's \"See You Again\", which plays over the film's emotional ending, received both popular and critical acclaim. It was shortlisted for the Song of the Year for the [[BBC Music Awards]] and was nominated for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] at the [[73rd Golden Globe Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Merry|first1=Stephanie|last2=Yahr|first2=Emily|title=Golden Globes nominations 2016: Complete list|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/arts-and-entertainment/wp/2015/12/10/golden-globes-nominations-2016-complete-coverage/|accessdate=December 10, 2015|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=December 10, 2015}}</ref> \"See You Again\" was the best selling-song of 2015 worldwide, with combined sales and track-equivalent streams of 20.9 million units according to [[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry|IFPI]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ifpi.org/downloads/GMR2016.pdf|title=IFPI Global Music Report|publisher=[[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry|IFPI]]|date=April 12, 2016|accessdate=April 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film, which began principal photography in September 2013, was originally designed as a July 11, 2014 release. It was put on hold following the fatal car crash that claimed Paul Walker's life on November 30, 2013. The production resumed in April 2014. In October 2014, Universal revealed that the film was officially titled ''Furious 7'', and that the debut trailer would be released during an interactive fan event over social media. In the days leading up to the event, seven-second, behind-the-scenes videos were released, titled \"7 Seconds of 7\".<ref name=\"OfficialTitle\">{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/fast-furious-7-official-title-trailer-release-date-1201339679/ |title='Fast & Furious 7' Gets Official Title, Sets Nov. 1 for Live Trailer Launch Event |last=Stedman |first=Alex |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=October 26, 2014 |accessdate=October 26, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6TcffdheY?url=http://variety.com/interstitial/ |archivedate=October 26, 2014 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref> On February 1, 2015, a new trailer featuring all-new footage debuted during [[Super Bowl XLIX]].\n\nThe film was next scheduled for release on April 10, 2015, but it was announced that the film's release date had been brought forward a week to April 3, 2015 (the same release date from the 2009 film ''[[Fast & Furious (2009 film)|Fast & Furious]]''). The official announcement in change of date was made in July 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://hollywoodreporter.com/news/fast-furious-7-release-date-716462|title='Fast & Furious 7' Release Date Shifts|last=Kilday|first=Gregg Webb|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=July 2, 2014|accessdate=July 2, 2014}}</ref> ''Furious 7'' premiered at the [[SXSW Film Festival]] at 12:07&nbsp;a.m. at Austin's [[The Paramount Theatre (Austin, Texas)|Paramount Theatre]] on March 16, 2015.<ref name=\"SXSW\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sxsw-furious-7-premiere-as-781575|title=SXSW: 'Furious 7' to Premiere as Secret Midnight Screening|first=Seth|last=Abramovitch|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=March 15, 2015|accessdate=March 16, 2015}}</ref> On March 27, 2015, a free standalone expansion for the video game ''[[Forza Horizon 2]]'', titled ''Forza Horizon 2 Presents Fast & Furious'', was released to help promote the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-02-25-forza-horizon-2-presents-fast-and-furious-is-a-standalone-expansion|title=Forza Horizon 2 Presents Fast & Furious is a standalone expansion|author=Wesley Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=February 25, 2015|accessdate=March 29, 2015}}</ref> For its global premiere at the [[TCL Chinese Theatre]] in [[Los Angeles]] on April 1, 2015, [[IMAX Corporation]] installed a new laser projection which was the first such installation in the U.S. and the second worldwide, following ''[[The Hobbit: The Battle of the Five Armies]]'', which opened at [[Scotiabank Theatre Toronto|Scotiabank Theatre]] in [[Toronto]] in December 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/imax-launch-laser-projection-technology-785806|title=Imax to Launch Laser Projection Technology at 'Furious 7' Global Premiere|author=Carolyn Giardina, Etan Vlessing|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=([[Prometheus Global Media]])|date=April 1, 2015|accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Unauthorized distribution===\nAccording to infringement tracking site ''Excipio'', the film was downloaded illegally 2.59 million times in four days (April 2\u20136) through various torrent sites with India being the top country for the illegal downloading with 578,000 downloads followed by Pakistan (321,000), China (289,000), the U.S. (251,000) and the UK (101,000).<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2015/digital/news/furious-7-piracy-2-6-million-downloads-1201467829/|title='Furious 7' Extremely Popular with Pirates|first=Todd|last=Spangler|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=April 7, 2015|accessdate=April 10, 2015}}</ref> A survey revealed that most Indians tended to resort to copyright violation due to lack of availability, [[Telecommunications in India|pricing concerns]], soaring internet costs and [[Censorship in India|censorship]], but the main reason being that most of the films are released months after their US dates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/english/hollywood/news/Fast-furious-7-downloads-India-tops-piracy-charts/articleshow/46973387.cms|title=Fast & Furious 7 downloads: India tops piracy charts|first=Sumeet|last=Keswani|work=[[The Times of India]]|publisher=([[The Times Group]])|date=April 19, 2015|accessdate=April 19, 2015}}</ref> It was illegally downloaded 44,794,877 times in 2015, making it the most pirated film released that year and the second most pirated film overall, behind ''[[Interstellar (film)|Interstellar]]'' which saw over 46.7 million illegal downloads the same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/digital/news/top-10-pirated-movies-of-2015-see-alarming-increase-in-downloads-1201667982/|title=Top 10 Pirated Movies of 2015 See Alarming Increase in Downloads|author=Andrew Wallenstein|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=December 27, 2016|accessdate=March 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Furious 7'' was released on 7 September 2015 in the UK and was released via [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]] on September 15, 2015 in other countries. The Blu-ray edition features an all new extended edition, deleted scenes, stunts, behind-the-scenes, and the music video for [[Wiz Khalifa]] and [[Charlie Puth]]'s \"[[See You Again (Wiz Khalifa song)|See You Again]]\". The Blu-ray and DVD version include behind-the-scene footage of the \"[[Race Wars]]\" scene including rapper [[Iggy Azalea]] and making of the cars featured in the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/dvd/trailers/452905-furious-7-extended-edition-coming-on-september-15|title=Furious 7 Extended Edition Coming on September 15|author=ComingSoon|work=ComingSoon.net|date=June 23, 2015|accessdate=June 23, 2015}}</ref> In the U.S. and Canada, it sold roughly 2.5 million units on Blu-ray and DVD in its first week of release, making it the highest-selling home entertainment live-action film of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/furious-7-grabs-more-50-826856|title='Furious 7' Grabs More Than $50 Million in Home Entertainment Debut|first=Gregg|last=Kilday|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=([[Prometheus Global Media]])|date=September 24, 2015|accessdate=September 24, 2015}}</ref> This record was later surpassed by ''[[Jurassic World]]'' the following month,<ref name=\"DVD\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/10/jurassic-world-dvd-vod-sales-records-furious-7-1201596549/|title='Jurassic World' Stomps On 'Furious 7' & Industry Home Entertainment Records|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=October 28, 2015|accessdate=October 29, 2015}}</ref> which in turn was surpassed by ''[[Star Wars: The Force Awakens]]'' by the end of the year.\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Furious 7'' made $353 million in the United States and Canada and $1.163 billion in other countries, for a worldwide total of $1.516 billion, against its $190 million production budget.<ref name=BOM /> Worldwide, it is the [[List of highest-grossing films|ninth highest-grossing film of all time]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/world/|title=WORLDWIDE GROSSES|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=January 5, 2016}}</ref> the [[2015 in film|third highest-grossing film of 2015]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2015|title=2015 WORLDWIDE GROSSES|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=January 5, 2016}}</ref> the highest-grossing film in [[The Fast and the Furious|''The Fast and the Furious'' franchise]] and the second highest-grossing Universal Pictures film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/world/?sort=studio&order=ASC&pagenum=5&p=.htm|title=WORLDWIDE GROSSES|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=May 3, 2015}}</ref> It was also the fastest film to reach the $1 billion mark at the time, doing so in 17 days;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=fastandthefurious.htm|title=The Fast and the Furious|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=April 12, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/04/12/weekend-box-office-furious-7-tops-800m-worldwide/|title=Box Office: 'Furious 7' Tops $800M Worldwide|first=Scott|last=Mendelson|magazine=[[Forbes]]|date=April 12, 2015|accessdate=April 12, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/jun/23/audiences-in-raptor-jurassic-world-hits-billion-dollar-milestone-in-record-time|title=Audiences in raptor: Jurassic World hits billion-dollar milestone in record time|last=Child|first=Ben|date=June 23, 2015|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|accessdate=June 23, 2015}}</ref> It is also the 20th film to gross over $1 billion. It also became the first film to pass 1 million in [[4DX]] admissions worldwide.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/will-4d-ever-catch-802627|title=Will 4D Ever Catch on?|first=Alex|last=Ritman|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=([[Prometheus Global Media]])|date=June 21, 2015|accessdate=June 21, 2015}}</ref> ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' calculated the net profit of the film to be $354{{nbsp}}million, when factoring together all expenses and revenues, making it the fifth most profitable release of 2015.<ref name=profit>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/furious-7-profit-box-office-2015-vin-diesel-paul-walker-1201724911/|title=No. 5 \u2018Furious 7\u2019 \u2013 2015 Most Valuable Movie Blockbuster Tournament|author=Mike Fleming Jr|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=March 23, 2016|accessdate=March 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWorldwide, ''Furious 7'' was released across 810 IMAX theaters, which was the largest worldwide rollout in IMAX's history,<ref name=\"VVV\">{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/furious-7-imax-release-1201464659/|title='Furious 7\u2032 Set for Widest Imax Release at 810 Locations|first=Dave|last=McNarry|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=April 1, 2015|accessdate=April 2, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"theforce2\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/12/star-wars-the-force-awakens-all-time-record-box-office-opening-1201666595/|title=Planet Earth Braces For 'Star Wars: The Force Awakens' To Make Intergalactic B.O. History|author=Anthony D'Alessandro, Nancy Tartaglione|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=December 14, 2015|accessdate=December 15, 2015}}</ref> Its worldwide opening of $397.6 million was the [[List of highest-grossing openings for films|fifth-highest opening of all time]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/world/worldwideopenings.htm|title=WORLDWIDE OPENINGS|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=May 1, 2015}}</ref> The film had an IMAX opening weekend total of $20.8 million.<ref name=\"OMG\"/> ''Furious 7'' also became the first of six films distributed by [[Universal Studios|Universal Pictures]] (alongside ''[[Jurassic World]]'', ''[[Minions (2015 film)|Minions]]'', ''[[The Fate of the Furious]]'', ''[[Despicable Me 3]]'' and ''[[Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom]]'') to earn more than $1 billion in its original run.\n\n====North America====\nPredictions for the opening weekend of ''Furious 7'' in the United States and Canada were continuously revised upwards, starting from $115 million to $150 million.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/furious-7-soaring-to-125-million-opening-weekend-in-u-s-1201466113/|title='Furious 7\u2032 Racing to Huge $140 Million Opening Weekend|first=Dave|last=McNarry|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=April 3, 2015|accessdate=April 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/box-office/furious-7%E2%80%B2-speeding-to-massive-150-million-opening-1201466351/|title='Furious 7\u2032 Speeding to Massive $150 Million Opening After $67.3 Million Friday Debut|first=Maane|last=Khatchatourian|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=April 4, 2015|accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref> It opened on Friday, April 3, 2015, across 4,004 theaters, including 365 IMAX theaters, which made it the widest opening for a ''Fast and Furious'' film and Universal's widest opening release ever (until first surpassed by ''Jurassic World'' and ''Minions'').<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/widest.htm?page=WIDESTOPEN&p=.htm|title=WIDEST RELEASES (or The 3,000+ Club)|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"THR\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-preview-furious-7-785485|title=Box-Office Preview: 'Furious 7' Revving Up for Record April Opening|first=Pamela|last=McClintock|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=March 31, 2015|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"DEAD\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/03/furious-7-universal-worldwide-box-office-opening-1201401923/|title='Furious 7\u2032 Racing Toward A $225M-$275M Global Opening \u2013 Box Office|author=Anthony D'Alessandro and Nancy Tartaglione|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=March 31, 2015|accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref> and earned $67.4 million, marking the tenth-biggest opening day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=4053|title=Friday Report: 'Furious 7' Scores Massive $67.3 Million on Opening Day|first=Ray|last=Subers|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|date=April 4, 2015|accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/days/?page=open&p=.htm|title=Opening Day Grosses|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref> The film's Friday gross included a $15.8 million late-night run (which began at 7 p.m.), from 3,069 theaters, marking Universal's highest late-night run, of which $2.2 million came from [[IMAX]] showings, marking the third largest IMAX preview gross ever.<ref name=\"THURSDAY\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/04/furious-7-supercharges-weekend-with-15-8m-thursday-preview-1201403822/|title='Furious 7\u2032 Supercharges Weekend With $15.8M Thursday Preview, $2.2M From IMAX|first=Anita|last=Busch|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 3, 2015|accessdate=April 3, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Thursday\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-jurassic-world-bites-802048|title=Box Office: 'Jurassic World' Bites Off $18.5 Million Thursday Night|first=Rebecca|last=Ford|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=([[Prometheus Global Media]])|date=June 12, 2015|accessdate=June 13, 2015}}</ref> Based on pure Friday gross (with the omission of revenues from Thursday shows), it earned $51.5 million, marking the fifth-biggest of all time.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/04/04/friday-box-office-furious-7-sprints-to-67-3m-could-nab-168m-weekend/|title=Box Office: 'Furious 7' Sprints To $67.3M Friday, Could Nab $168M Weekend|first=Scott|last=Mendelson|magazine=[[Forbes]]|date=April 4, 2015|accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/05/02/box-office-avengers-2-assembles-mere-84-46m-friday/|title='Avengers 2' Box Office: 'Age Of Ultron' Assembles 'Mere' $84M Friday|first=Scott|last=Mendelson|work=[[Forbes]]|date=May 2, 2015|accessdate=May 2, 2015}}</ref> Through Sunday, April 5, it had an opening weekend total of $147.1 million, breaking the record for the biggest April opening (the record was later broken in 2018 by ''[[Avengers: Infinity War]]'' with $257.7 million),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/weekends/month/?mo=04&p=.htm|title=TOP OPENING WEEKENDS BY MONTH \u2013 April|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=April 11, 2015}}</ref> the biggest opening in the ''Fast & Furious'' franchise, the biggest Easter opening (the record was broken a year later by ''[[Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice]]''{{'}}s opening gross of $166 million),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/weekends/easter.htm|title=EASTER OPENINGS|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref> the [[List of highest-grossing openings for films|fourth-biggest opening of 2015]], the third biggest pre-summer opening ever,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/04/furious-7-box-office-opening-weekend-easter-1201404191/|title='Furious 7\u2032 Final Box Office Tally $147.1M, Ends Race Beyond Expectations After Record-Breaking Bow|first=Anita|last=Busch|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 5, 2015|accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref> and the thirteenth-biggest opening of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/grossbydays.htm?days=3&p=.htm|title=TOP OPENING GROSSES BY DAYS IN RELEASE (3 DAYS)|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref> It earned an IMAX opening weekend total of $13.3 million, marking the second-biggest of all time for a 2D movie.<ref name=\"BOX\">{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=4054&p=.htm|title=Weekend Report: 'Furious 7' Opens to $384 Million Worldwide|first=Ray|last=Subers|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|date=April 5, 2015|accessdate=April 6, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-furious-7-debuts-786433|title=Box Office: 'Furious 7' Debuts With Record $392.3M Worldwide|first=Pamela|last=McClintock|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=April 5, 2016|accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref> Premium large format comprised 8% ($11.5 million) of the total opening gross from 400 PLF screens, which is the biggest 2D PLF opening.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/04/05/box-office-furious-7-races-to-384m-worldwide-bow/|title=Box Office: 'Furious 7' Races To Near-Record $384M Worldwide Bow|first=Scott|last=Mendelson|magazine=[[Forbes]]|date=April 5, 2015|accessdate=April 6, 2015}}</ref> It was Universal's fastest film to reach the $200 million mark at the time, doing so in eight days.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/box-office/furious-7%E2%80%B2-heads-for-60-2-million-weekend-crossing-250-million-mark-1201470776///|title='Furious 7\u2032 Heads for $60.2 Million Weekend, Crossing $250 Million Mark|first=Maane|last=Khatchatourian|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=April 11, 2015|accessdate=April 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/box-office-furious-7-dominates-competition-with-60-6-million-1201470903/|title=Box Office: 'Furious 7\u2032 Dominates Competition With $60.6 Million|first=Brent|last=Lang|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=April 12, 2015|accessdate=April 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn its [[Second weekend in box office performance|second weekend]], the film expanded to 4,022 theaters, thereby breaking its own record of being the widest Universal Pictures release ever, and earned an estimated $59.6 million, declining by 60%, which is the third best second weekend holdover for a pre-summer film release.<ref name=\"SW\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/04/furious-7-the-longest-ride-nicholas-sparks-box-office-1201408312/|title='Furious 7\u2032 Slower In Actuals; Still Highest Grossing Title In Series \u2013 Box Office|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 13, 2015|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=4055&p=.htm|title=Weekend Report: 'Furious 7' Repeats, Sets Opening Day Record in China|first=Ray|last=Subers|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|date=April 12, 2015|accessdate=April 13, 2015}}</ref> It became the highest-grossing film in the ''Fast & Furious'' franchise, doing so only in ten days (the previous record which was held by ''Fast & Furious 6'' took fifteen weeks to reach its entire lifetime gross of $238.67 million).<ref name=\"SW\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-furious-7-hits-787983|title=Box Office: 'Furious 7' Hits Historic $252.5M; 'Longest Ride' No. 3|first=Pamela|last=McClintock|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=([[Prometheus Global Media]])|date=April 12, 2015|accessdate=April 12, 2015}}</ref> It also set the record for the biggest second-weekend April gross.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2015/04/12/furious-7-longest-ride-box-office-weekend/25668361/|title='Furious' goes into box-office cruise control|first=Patrick|last=Ryan|work=[[USA Today]]|date=April 12, 2015|accessdate=April 12, 2015}}</ref> It topped the box office for four consecutive weekends,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-furious-7-fends-791454|title=Box Office: 'Furious 7' Fends Off 'Age of Adaline' Challenge to Remain on Top|author=Gregg Kilday, Jay A. Fernandez|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=([[Prometheus Global Media]])|date=April 26, 2015|accessdate=April 26, 2015}}</ref> becoming the first film to top the box office for four consecutive weekends since ''[[The Hunger Games (film)|The Hunger Games]]'' in March 2012 and one of only 29 films since 1985 to have had four straight box office wins during their theatrical runs, although this highly depends on many factors, including the release time and the competition around.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/furious-7-box-office-age-of-adaline-1201480114/|title=Box Office: 'Furious 7\u2032 Races Past 'Age of Adaline'|first=Brent|last=Lang|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=([[Penske Media Corporation]])|date=April 26, 2015|accessdate=April 26, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2015/04/26/furious-7-age-of-adaline-box-office/26396251/|title='Furious 7' rolls to fourth No. 1 weekend'|first=Brian|last=Truitt|work=[[USA Today]]|date=April 26, 2015|accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref> It ended its theatrical run on July 24, 2015, playing in theaters for a total of 112 days<ref name=\"BOM\"/> and became the [[List of highest-grossing films in Canada and the United States|thirty-first highest-grossing film of all time]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/domestic.htm|title=DOMESTIC GROSSES|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=January 5, 2016}}</ref> the fifth highest-grossing film of 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?yr=2015&p=.htm|title=2015 DOMESTIC GROSSES|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=January 5, 2016}}</ref> the highest-grossing film in ''The Fast and the Furious'' franchise,<ref name=\"Series\">{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=fastandthefurious.htm|title=The Fast and the Furious|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=February 7, 2016}}</ref> the second highest-grossing Universal film of 2015 (behind ''Jurassic World'' and ''Minions''),<ref name=\"Uni\"/> and the fifth highest-grossing film distributed by Universal.<ref name=\"Uni\">{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/studio/chart/?studio=universal.htm|title=Universal Pictures All-Time Domestic Grosses|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=April 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Outside North America====\nOutside the US and Canada, the film became the third highest-grossing film,<ref name=\"UNI\">{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/world/?pagenum=1&sort=osgross&order=DESC&p=.htm|title=Worldwide Grosses|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=April 19, 2015}}</ref>\nthe highest-grossing Universal distributed film,<ref name=\"UNI\"/> and the highest-grossing 2015 film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2015&sort=osgross&order=DESC&p=.htm|title=2015 Worldwide Grosses|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=April 19, 2015}}</ref> On April 26, 2015, it became the third film in cinematic history to earn over $1 billion overseas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/04/furious-7-billion-dollars-international-box-office-universal-highest-grossing-movie-in-china-1201416583/|title='Furious 7\u2032 Crosses $1B Overseas; Passes 'T4\u2032 In China As Top-Grossing Film Ever|first=Nancy|last=Tartaglione|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 26, 2015|accessdate=April 26, 2015}}</ref> It opened on Wednesday, April 1, 2015, in 12 countries, earning $16.9 million (including previews from 22 countries).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/04/furious-7-box-office-international-1201403421/|title='Furious 7\u2032 Roars To $16.9M In Overseas Debut, Pacing 60% Ahead Of Predecessor|first=Nancy|last=Tartaglione|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 2, 2015|accessdate=April 3, 2015}}</ref> It opened in 33 more countries on Thursday, April 2, for a total of 45 countries, earning $43 million from 8,407 screens, marking Universal Pictures overseas' highest-grossing Thursday ever, and for a two-day total of $60 million.<ref name=\"OVERSEAS2\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/04/furious-7-box-office-international-1201403421/|title='Furious 7\u2032 Races To $60M After Two Days At International Box Office \u2013 Update|first=Nancy|last=Tartaglione|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 3, 2015|accessdate=April 4, 2015}}</ref> It added 20 more countries on Friday, April 3, earning $59.2 million from 9,935 screens in 63 countries, for a three-day total of $120.6 million.<ref name=\"FRIDAY\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/04/furious-7-box-office-international-1201403421/|title='Furious 7\u2032 Clocks $120.6M Offshore After Uni's Biggest Fri Ever \u2013 Intl B.O. Update|first=Nancy|last=Tartaglione|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 4, 2015|accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"THRG\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/foreign-box-office-furious-7-786010|title=Foreign Box Office: 'Furious 7' Roars Past $100M; 'Fifty Shades' Hits $400M|first=Pamela|last=McClintock|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=April 4, 2015|accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref> The film set all-time opening-day records in 15 countries including Argentina, Chile, Colombia, Mexico, India, Indonesia, the Middle East and Thailand,<ref name=\"OVERSEAS2\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-furious-7-fires-786010|title=Box Office: 'Furious 7' Fires Up Overseas With $16.9M|first=Pamela|last=McClintock|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=April 2, 2015|accessdate=April 3, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/furious-7-international-box-office-1201465525/|title=Box Office: 'Furious 7\u2032 Launches with $16.9 Million Overseas|first=Dave|last=McNarry|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=April 2, 2015|accessdate=April 3, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://m.indiatoday.in/story/furious-7-sets-new-box-office-records-in-india/1/428509.html|title=Furious 7 sets new box office records in India, collects Rs 12 crore on opening|first=Mail|last=Today|magazine=[[India Today]]|date=April 5, 2015|accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"India\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/india-box-office-furious-7-788293|title=India Box Office: 'Furious 7' Races Ahead|first=Nyay|last=Bhushan|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=([[Prometheus Global Media]])|date=April 13, 2015|accessdate=April 13, 2015}}</ref> and opening day records for Universal Pictures in 40 countries including Australia, Brazil, Germany, Italy and Mexico.<ref name=\"FRIDAY\"/> Through Sunday, April 5, it earned a 4-day opening weekend total of $250.4 million from 10,683 screens in 64 countries, which is the fourth-highest international opening ever, in all which it reached first place at the box office<ref name=\"OMG\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/04/furious-7-box-office-international-1201403421/|title='F7\u2032 Grabs $5M Bigger Purse For Monster $245M Opening \u2013 International Box Office|first=Nancy|last=Tartaglione|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 6, 2015|accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"BOX\"/><ref name=\"OMGG\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/04/furious-7-box-office-international-1201403421/|title='Furious 7\u2032 Roars To $245M International Box Office; Mexico, UK Lead \u2013 Actuals|first=Nancy|last=Tartaglione|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 6, 2015|accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/intl/weekend/opening/|title=OVERSEAS TOTAL ALL TIME OPENINGS|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=April 26, 2015}}</ref> It earned an IMAX opening weekend total of $7.5 million from 175 IMAX screens, breaking the record for the biggest April IMAX gross, previously held by ''The Winter Soldier'' ($6.43 million).<ref name=\"OMG\"/> It set opening weekend records in 29 countries including Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Colombia, Egypt, Malaysia, Mexico, Middle East, Romania, Taiwan, Thailand, Venezuela and Vietnam.<ref name=\"OMG\"/><ref name=\"OMGG\"/> In its second weekend, it held the top spot and fell gradually by 20.4% to $198.7 million (including China's opening day gross) from 18,374 screens in 66 territories as a result of minor competition, and remaining at number one in all 63 territories where it was released the previous week. It added three new countries in its second weekend; China, Russia and Poland.<ref name=\"I2\"/> Earning $167.9 million in its third weekend, it topped the box office outside of North America for three consecutive weekends,<ref name=\"I3\"/> until surpassed by ''[[Avengers: Age of Ultron]]'' in its fourth weekend.<ref name=\"overseas1\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/04/international-box-office-avengers-age-of-ultron-furious-7-paul-blart-home-1201416588/|title='Avengers: Age Of Ultron' Blasts Off With $201.2M At International Box Office|first=Nancy|last=Tartaglione|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 26, 2015|accessdate=April 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe film was a massive box office hit in China. It opened there on April 12 and set an all-time midnight run record with $8.05 million<ref name=\"I2\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/china-box-office-furious-7-788000|title=China Box Office: 'Furious 7' Takes Record $8.05M in Sunday Midnight Screenings|first=Clifford|last=Coonan|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=([[Prometheus Global Media]])|date=April 12, 2015|accessdate=April 12, 2015}}</ref> and an opening day record with $68.8 million.<ref name=\"I2\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/04/international-box-office-furious-7-china-record-longest-ride-insurgent-paul-blart-1201408563/|title='Furious 7\u2032 Box Office Hits $801.5M Global; 'Paul Blart 2\u2032, 'Longest Ride' New Overseas\n|first=Nancy|last=Tartaglione|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 13, 2015|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/furious-7-box-office-record-1201470938/|title=Box Office: 'Furious 7\u2032 Tops $800 Million Globally in Less Than 2 Weeks|first=Brent|last=Lang|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=April 12, 2015|accessdate=April 12, 2015}}</ref> Its opening day included a record breaking $5 million from IMAX run (also breaking ''Transformers 4''{{'}}s former record of $3.4 million).<ref name=\"I2\"/> Through its opening week (April 12\u201319), it earned $245.9 million.<ref name=\"I3\"/><ref name=\"250M\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/global-box-office-furious-7-789983|title=Global Box Office: 'Furious 7' Hits $1.15B, Including Massive $250.5M in China|first=Pamela|last=McClintock|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=([[Prometheus Global Media]])|date=April 19, 2015|accessdate=April 19, 2015}}</ref> For the weekend alone, it took in $88.7 million from 5,454 screens (Friday to Sunday) and $182.4 million (Monday to Sunday) at the Chinese box office. It grossed {{CNY|link=yes|1}} billion in five days\u2014the fastest time in which that has been achieved\u2014and soon became the [[List of highest-grossing films in China|highest-grossing foreign film ever in China]].<ref name=\"I3\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/04/international-box-office-furious-7-child-44-cinderella-dragonball-z-1201412508/|title='Furious 7\u2032 Drives To $1.12B Global To Bust Records in China; 'Dragon Ball' Trumps 'F7\u2032 In Japan \u2013 Intl B.O. Update\n|author=Nancy Tartaglione and Anita Busch|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=([[Penske Media Corporation]])|date=April 20, 2015|accessdate=April 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"250M\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/intl/china/opening/|title=CHINA ALL TIME OPENINGS|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=April 29, 2015}}</ref> In 15 days, its gross in China surpassed those in Canada and the United States<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pro.boxoffice.com/latest-news/2015-04-26-global-report-avengers-age-of-ultron-off-to-hot-start-furious-7-crosses-1-billion-overseas-becomes-1-movie-of-all-time-in-china|title=GLOBAL REPORT: 'Avengers: Age Of Ultron' Off To Hot Start, 'Furious 7' Crosses $1 Billion Overseas; Becomes #1 Movie Of All-Time In China|first=Jonathan|last=Papish|work=pro.boxoffice.com|date=April 26, 2015|accessdate=April 27, 2015}}</ref> and became the first film in China to make more than 2 billion [[renminbi]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/china-box-office-furious-7-791923|title=China Box Office: 'Furious 7' Becomes Highest-Grossing Movie Ever|first=Clifford|last=Coonan|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=([[Prometheus Global Media]])|date=April 27, 2015|accessdate=April 29, 2015}}</ref> Its success has been credited to [[China Film Group Corporation]], the state-owned film distributor, which had invested considerably in the film, reportedly taking a 10% stake.<ref name=\"NYT China story\">{{cite news|last=Qin|first=Amy|title='Furious 7' Becomes China's Most Successful Movie Ever|url=http://sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/04/29/furious-7-becomes-chinas-most-successful-movie-ever/?hpw&rref=arts&action=click&pgtype=Homepage&module=well-region&region=bottom-well&WT.nav=bottom-well&_r=0|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 30, 2015|accessdate=April 30, 2015|quote='While it's not unprecedented for films that do moderately well in North America to do even better in China' wrote Rob Cain on his website ''China Film Biz'', citing the 2013 [[Guillermo del Toro]] film ''[[Pacific Rim (film)|Pacific Rim]]'' as an example, 'never before has a bona fide American smash hit exceeded its own domestic gross in a foreign territory'}}</ref>\n\nThe largest openings outside North America and China occurred in Mexico ($21.5 million), the UK, Ireland and Malta ($18.7 million), Germany ($15.9 million), Russia and the CIS ($15.9 million), Brazil ($11.4 million), France ($11.4 million), Australia ($11.3 million), Taiwan ($10.3 million), Argentina ($9.3 million), Korea ($8.9 million), India ($8.7 million), Italy ($8.2 million), Malaysia ($7.3 million), Spain ($6.3 million), Venezuela ($6 million), Thailand ($6 million), Colombia ($5.2 million)<ref name=\"OMGG\"/><ref name=\"I2\"/> and Pakistan ($2.4 million). In the UAE, where parts of the film was shot, it opened with $4.8 million.<ref name=\"OMGG\"/> Out of the 68 countries it was released in, the only country not to open at number one was Japan (locally released with the title, ''Wild Speed: Skymission'') where it earned $6.2 million in its opening weekend, behind ''[[Dragon Ball Z: Resurrection 'F']]'' ($7.6 million).<ref name=\"I3\"/> and ''[[Detective Conan: Sunflowers of Inferno]]'' ($7.4 million).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/japan-box-office-furious-7-790130|title=Japan Box Office: 'Furious 7' Opens in Third, Hits Franchise-Best Numbers|author=Gavin J. Blair|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=([[Prometheus Global Media]])|date=April 19, 2015|accessdate=April 20, 2015}}</ref> It became the highest-grossing film of all time in Argentina, Colombia, Ecuador, Indonesia, Malaysia, South Africa, the UAE, Uruguay, Trinidad and Vietnam and Universal Pictures' highest-grossing film of all time in 29 countries including Argentina, China, Ecuador, Egypt, India, Indonesia, Lebanon, Malaysia, Mexico, Paraguay, Peru, Thailand, Turkey, UAE and Vietnam.<ref name=\"I3\"/> In Latin America, it became the second highest-grossing film ($200 million), the first time Universal has reached the milestone and the second film in history to earn more than $200 million after ''The Avengers''.<ref name=\"PP2\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/05/international-box-office-pitch-perfect-2-australia-avengers-age-of-ultron-furious-7-hot-pursuit-1201423936/|title='Pitch Perfect 2\u2032 Sings, Soars Down Under; 'Ultron' Adds $68.3M \u2013 Intl Box Office|first=Nancy|last=Tartaglione|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=([[Penske Media Corporation]])|date=May 10, 2015|accessdate=May 10, 2015}}</ref> In total earnings, the largest countries outside the U.S. and Canada are China ($391.2 million), the UK, Ireland and Malta ($60 million), Mexico ($50.9 million), Brazil, ($46.5 million) and Germany ($40.3 million).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Furious-7|title=Furious 7 \u2014 International gross|website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=July 15, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/uk-box-office-up-midyear-809408|title=U.K. Box Office Up 9 Percent Mid-Year|first=Alex|last=Ritman|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=([[Prometheus Global Media]])|date=July 17, 2015|accessdate=July 17, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"highest\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/09/china-monster-hunt-all-time-china-record-beats-furious-7-1201522646/|title='Monster Hunt' Overtakes 'F7' As All-Time China Box Office Champ In 2-Month Run|first=Nancy|last=Tartaglione|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=([[Penske Media Corporation]])|date=September 12, 2015|accessdate=September 12, 2015}}</ref> It grossed a total of $39 million in IMAX ticket sales in China, the biggest ever in the market.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/imax-china-install-100-new-869443|title=Imax China to Install 100 New Screens in 2016, Bullish on Growth|author=Patrick Brzeski|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=February 24, 2016|accessdate=February 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n''Furious 7'' received positive reviews, with critics praising the film's action set pieces, performances, and its poignant tribute to Walker.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kelley|first1=Sonaiya|title=''Furious 7'' opens to overwhelmingly positive reviews from critics|url=http://mashable.com/2015/04/04/critics-reactions-furious-7/#tkRuHDbjWmqY|accessdate=November 26, 2017|work=[[Mashable]]|date=April 5, 2015}}</ref> Review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports an 81% rating based on 265 reviews, and an average rating of 6.69/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"Serving up a fresh round of over-the-top thrills while adding unexpected dramatic heft, ''Furious 7'' keeps the franchise moving in more ways than one.\"<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\"/> On [[Metacritic]] the film has a score of 67 out of 100, based on 44 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/furious-7|title=''Furious 7'' Reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref> In [[CinemaScore]] polls conducted during the opening weekend, cinema audiences gave ''Furious 7'' an average grade of \"A\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lang|first1=Brent|title=Box Office: 'Furious 7' Destroys Records With $143.6 Million Debut|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/furious-7-box-office-debut-1201466584/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Variety|agency=Penske Media Corporation|date=April 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe film received highly positive reviews upon release at a secret screening at the [[South by Southwest|2015 SXSW Film Festival]] on March 16, 2015. Ramin Setoodeh of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' noted that fans started lining up outside four hours before the film was scheduled to start. The film closed with a tribute to Walker, which left many in the theater \"holding back tears\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/furious-7-premieres-at-sxsw-to-cheers-for-paul-walker-1201453405/|title='Furious 7\u2032 Premieres at SXSW to Cheers for Paul Walker|first=Ramin|last=Setoodah|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 16, 2015|accessdate=March 16, 2015}}</ref> Critic Dave Palmer gave the film 7/10, saying, \"''Furious 7'' is the type of movie Michael Bay has spent his entire career trying to make: filled with shots of scantily clad women, fast cars, and clever one liners\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.gatehousemedia.com/davidpalmer/?p=891 |title=\"Furious 7\" More Over-the-Top Fun |website=The Reel Deal |accessdate=April 4, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150410112219/http://blogs.gatehousemedia.com/davidpalmer/?p=891 |archive-date=April 10, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[A.O. Scott]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' gave the film two and a half stars out of five and said, \"''Furious 7'' extends its predecessors' inclusive, stereotype-resistant ethic. Compared to almost any other large-scale, big-studio enterprise, the ''Furious'' brand practices a slick, no-big-deal multiculturalism, and nods to both feminism and domestic traditionalism.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nytimes.com/2015/04/03/movies/review-in-furious-7-a-franchise-continues-to-roar.html?referrer=&_r=0|title=Review: In 'Furious 7,' a Franchise Continues to Roar|author=A.O. Scott|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 1, 2015|accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nJohn DeFore of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' criticized the film however, describing it as \"stupidly diverting\", saying the running time was \"overinflated\"; he compared watching the film to a morbid game, in addition to criticizing the screenplay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.hollywoodreporter.com/entry/view/id/929602|title='Furious 7': SXSW Review|first=John|last=DeFore|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=March 16, 2015|accessdate=March 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width: 99%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Award / Film Festival\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Recipient(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\"| 2015\n| rowspan=\"8\"| [[2015 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Awards]]\n| [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie - Action|Choice Movie: Action]]\n!\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"8\"| <ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/teen-choice-awards-winners-2015-full-list-1201571268/|title=2015 Teen Choice Award Winners \u2013 Full List|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|date=August 16, 2015|accessdate=August 17, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Choice Movie Actor: Action\n| [[Vin Diesel]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Paul Walker]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Choice Movie Actress: Action\n| [[Michelle Rodriguez]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Jordana Brewster]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie Villain|Choice Movie: Villain]]\n| [[Jason Statham]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Choice Movie: Chemistry\n| Vin Diesel, Paul Walker, Michelle Rodriguez, [[Tyrese Gibson]], [[Dwayne Johnson]], [[Ludacris]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Choice Music: Song from a Movie or TV Show\n| \"[[See You Again (Wiz Khalifa song)|See You Again]]\" by [[Wiz Khalifa]] ft. [[Charlie Puth]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"18\"| 2016\n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[42nd People's Choice Awards|People's Choice Awards]]\n| Favorite Movie\n!\n| {{won}}\n|rowspan=\"4\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peopleschoice.com/pca/awards/nominees/index.jsp?year=2016|title=2016 Nominees & Winners|work=People's Choice Awards|accessdate=October 3, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| Favorite Action Movie\n!\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Favorite Action Movie Actor\n| Vin Diesel\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Favorite Action Movie Actress\n| Michelle Rodriguez\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[21st Critics' Choice Awards|Critics' Choice Awards]]\n| Best Original Song\n| \"See You Again\"\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"2\"|<ref>[http://www.criticschoice.com/movie-awards/ The Critics\u2019 Choice Movie Awards are bestowed annually by the Broadcast Film Critics Association to honor the finest in cinematic achievement] {{webarchive |url=https://www.webcitation.org/6CrNMCA0g?url=http://www.criticschoice.com/movie-awards/ |date=2012-12-12 }}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Action Movie\n!\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[73rd Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Awards]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]]\n| \"See You Again\"\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite news|last1=Merry|first1=Stephanie|last2=Yahr|first2=Emily|title=Golden Globes nominations 2016: Complete list|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/arts-and-entertainment/wp/2015/12/10/golden-globes-nominations-2016-complete-coverage/|accessdate=December 10, 2015|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=December 10, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Houston Film Critics Society Awards 2015|Houston Film Critics Society]]\n| Best Original Song\n| \"See You Again\"\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awardsdaily.com/2015/12/13/houston-film-critics-nominations/|title=Houston Film Critics Society Nominations|date=December 13, 2015|website=Awardsdaily.com|accessdate=August 30, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[22nd Screen Actors Guild Awards|Screen Actors Guild Awards]]\n| Outstanding Performance by a Stunt Ensemble in a Motion Picture\n!\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref name=\"sag1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sagawards.org/media-pr/press-releases/key-deadlines-and-dates-22nd-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards%C2%AE-announced|title=Key Deadlines and Dates for 22nd Annual Screen Actors Guild Awards\u00ae Announced|publisher=sagawards.org|accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref><ref name=\"sag2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sagawards.org/media-pr/press-releases/stunt-performers-%E2%80%9Cmad-max-fury-road%E2%80%9D-and-%E2%80%9Cgame-thrones%E2%80%9D-announced-22nd|title=Stunt Performers from \"Mad Max: Fury Road\" and \"Game of Thrones\" Announced as 22nd Screen Actors Guild Awards\u00ae honorees for Outstanding Action Performances by Film and Television Stunt Ensembles|publisher=sagawards.org|accessdate=2016-01-30}}</ref>\n|-\n| Las Vegas Film Critics Society\n| Best Original Song\n| \"See You Again\"\n| {{won}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awardsdaily.com/2015/12/17/spotlight-sweeps-las-vegas-film-critics-awards/|title=Spotlight sweeps Las Vegas Film Critics Awards|date=December 17, 2015|website=Awardsdaily.com|accessdate=August 30, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[2016 MTV Movie Awards|MTV Movie Awards]]\n| Best Action Performance\n| Vin Diesel\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\"|<ref>{{cite web|author=Author Jamie Lovett @JamieLovett |url=https://comicbook.com/2016/03/08/deadpool-avengers-and-star-wars-nominated-for-mtv-movie-awards/|title=Deadpool, Avengers, And Star Wars Nominated For MTV Movie Awards |publisher=Comicbook.com|date=2016-03-08}}</ref>\n|-\n| Ensemble Cast\n!\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[20th Satellite Awards|Satellite Awards]]\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]]\n| \"See You Again\"\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressacademy.com/award_cat/2015/|work=[[International Press Academy]]|at=pressacademy.com|title=Satellite Awards (2015)|publisher=[[International Press Academy|IPA]]|accessdate=December 2, 2015|date=December 2, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=3| [[42nd Saturn Awards|Saturn Award]]\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Action or Adventure Film|Best Action or Adventure Film]]\n!\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=3| <ref name=\"Saturn 42\">{{cite web|url=http://www.saturnawards.org/|title=The 42nd Annual Saturn Awards nominations are announced for 2016!|publisher=[[Saturn Award]]s|date=February 24, 2016|accessdate=March 4, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Editing|Best Editing]]\n| [[Christian Wagner]], Dylan Highsmith, Kirk Morri, and Leigh Folsom Boyd\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best DVD or Blu-ray Special Edition Release|Best DVD or Blu-ray Special Edition Release]]\n| ''Furious 7 (Extended Edition)''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[St. Louis Gateway Film Critics Association]]\n| Best Original Song\n| \"See You Again\"\n| {{draw|Runner-up}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awardsdaily.com/2015/12/14/st-louis-film-critics-nominations-3/|title=St Louis Film Critics nominations|date=December 14, 2015|website=Awardsdaily.com|accessdate=August 30, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Visual Effects Society Awards 2015|Visual Effects Society]]\n| Outstanding Visual Effects in a Photoreal Feature\n| Mike Wassel, Karen Murphy, [[Martin Hill (visual effects artist)|Martin Hill]], Kevin McIlwain, [[Dan Sudick]]\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/in-contention/star-wars-the-force-awakens-game-of-thrones-peanuts-movie-visual-effects-society-award-nominations-1201677466/|title='Star Wars,' 'Game of Thrones,' 'The Peanuts Movie' Lead Visual Effects Society Nominations|first=Margaret|last=Lenker|date=January 12, 2016|website=Variety.com|accessdate=August 30, 2017}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Sequel==\n{{Main|The Fate of the Furious}}\nRegarding a possible sequel, Vin Diesel said:\n\n<blockquote>I was trying to keep it close to the vest throughout the release. Paul Walker used to say that [an eighth film] was guaranteed. And in some ways, when your brother guarantees something, you sometimes feel like you have to make sure it comes to pass ... so if fate has it, then you'll get this when you hear about it. [''Furious 7''] was for Paul, [the eighth film] is from Paul.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/2015/04/13/vin-diesel-says-furious-7-was-for-paul-and-8-will-be-from-paul/|title=Vin Diesel Says Furious 7 Was For Paul And 8 Will Be From Paul|first=Joe|last=Comicbook|work=Comicbook.com}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nDiesel further hinted at an eighth film on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'' when he stated that Kurt Russell's character would span multiple films. He also stated that the film would take place in [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/fast-and-furious-8-setting-kurt-russell/|title=Vin Diesel Teases Fast and Furious 8 Setting In New York|work=Slashfilm|date=March 31, 2015|accessdate=March 31, 2015}}</ref> Chris Morgan wrote his sixth script in the franchise, while Neal H. Moritz returned to produce. Moritz later stated, \"[The story] is going to have to be something enticing for all of us ... it has to be as good as or better [than ''Furious 7'']\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/fast-8-nowhere-starting-line-787045 | title='Fast 8' Nowhere Near Starting Line | work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=April 8, 2015 | accessdate=April 21, 2015 | author=Rebecca Ford and Borys Kit}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2015 [[CinemaCon]] in [[Las Vegas]], Diesel announced the film for an April 14, 2017 release date.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/furious-8-gets-2017-release-791103|title='Furious 8' Gets 2017 Release Date|author=Rebecca Ford|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=([[Prometheus Global Media]])|date=April 23, 2015|accessdate=April 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/furious-8-to-debut-april-14-2017-1201478792/|title='Furious 8' to Debut April 14, 2017|author=Brent Lang|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=([[Penske Media Corporation]])|date=April 23, 2015|accessdate=April 24, 2015}}</ref> On August 16, 2015, at the [[2015 Teen Choice Awards]] (where ''Furious 7'' received the award for [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie - Action|Choice Movie \u2013 Action]] and Walker received the award for Choice Movie Actor \u2013 Action), Diesel gave the film the initial title ''Fast 8''.<ref>{{cite web|last=O'Connell|first=Sean|title=Vin Diesel Just Dropped The Name Of The Next Fast & Furious Movie|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/new/Vin-Diesel-Just-Dropped-Name-Next-Fast-Furious-Movie-77617.html|work=Cinema Blend|date=August 17, 2015|accessdate=August 20, 2015}}</ref> In September 2015, Diesel stated that the script had almost been completed,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Busch|first1=Anita|title=Will Vin Diesel Direct 'Furious 8'?|url=https://deadline.com/2015/10/vin-diesel-furious-8-director-universal-1201558992/|accessdate=October 7, 2015|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=October 1, 2015}}</ref> and expressed interest in [[Rob Cohen]], who directed the [[The Fast and the Furious (2001 film)|first film]], to direct the eighth installment.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vin Diesel Wants Rob Cohen to Direct Furious 8|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/618557-vin-diesel-wants-rob-cohen-to-direct-furious-8|accessdate=October 4, 2015|work=comingsoon.net|date=October 1, 2015}}</ref> On October 14, 2015, Diesel announced on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]'' that ''[[Straight Outta Compton (film)|Straight Outta Compton]]'' director [[F. Gary Gray]] would direct the film.<ref>{{cite news|last=Silver|first=Stephen|title=Fast and Furious 8: Vin Diesel Re-Confirms New York Setting|url=https://screenrant.com/fast-and-furious-8-new-york-setting-vin-diesel/|work=ScreenRant|date=October 16, 2015|accessdate=October 16, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=VIDEO: Vin Diesel Reveals Setting & Director for 'FAST 8' on Tonight Show|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/VIDEO-Vin-Diesel-Reveals-Setting-Director-for-FAST-8-on-Tonight-Show-20151015|work=BWW TV World|date=October 15, 2015|accessdate=October 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, Moritz said that Walker's character, Brian O'Conner, would not appear in the film, following the use of [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] in the previous film after Walker's death in 2013, with Moritz stating that his character had \"moved on\".<ref name=\"Characters\">{{cite web|last=Yaniz|first=Robert, Jr.|title='Furious 8' Producer Discusses Continuing Without Paul Walker|url=https://screenrant.com/fast-furious-8-paul-walker/|work=Screen Rant|date=July 22, 2015|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref> It had previously been reported that Paul's younger brother, Cody Walker, would either join the cast in a new role,<ref>{{cite web|last=Jordan|first=Shane|title='Fast and Furious 8' Paul Walker Brother Cody Cast in New Role?|url=http://www.classicalite.com/articles/23888/20150613/fast-furious-8-paul-walker-brother-cody-cast-new-role.htm|work=Classicalite|date=June 13, 2015|accessdate=July 3, 2015}}</ref> or replace his older brother in the role of O'Conner;<ref>{{cite web|last=Monalo|first=Komfie|title=Fast and Furious 8 Release Date, Cast: Will Cody Walker Replace Paul Walker (Brian O'Conner)?|url=http://www.gospelherald.com/articles/56362/20150702/fast-furious-8-release-date-cast-will-cody-walker-replace-paul-brian-oconnor.htm|work=Gospel Herald|date=July 2, 2013|accessdate=July 3, 2015}}</ref> however, it was later announced that the character will not return to the franchise.<ref>{{cite web|last=Agpalo|first=Jaja|title='Fast and Furious 8' Release Date & Cast: Cody Walker Not Returning; Will The Plot Still Include Paul Walker? Plus, Other Details We Know [VIDEO]|url=http://www.foodworldnews.com/articles/52975/20151112/fast-furious-8-release-date-cast-cody-walker-returning-will.htm|work=Food World News|date=November 12, 2015|accessdate=December 1, 2015}}</ref> Moritz also said that the film would shift the focus of the franchise from a series of [[heist film]]s to a [[Spy film|spy caper]], following a similar change in focus from [[street racing]] in ''[[Fast Five]]'' (2011).<ref>{{cite web|last=Sokol|first=Tony|title=Fast & Furious 8 Movie Casting News: 'Fast and Furious 8' Will Begin New Trilogy As Soon As They Find A Director, Which Hinges On Finding Screenplay|url=http://www.kpopstarz.com/articles/226898/20150803/fast-furious-8-movie-casting-news-will-begin-new-trilogy.htm|work=KpopStarz|date=August 3, 2015|accessdate=August 4, 2015}}</ref> In December 2016, the film was retitled ''The Fate of the Furious''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/fast-8-retitled-fate-of-the-furious-trailer-teaser-arrives/|title=Fast 8 Retitled Fate of the Furious; Trailer Teaser Arrives|work=Screen Rant|date=December 9, 2016|accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Film}}\n* [[List of films featuring drones]]\n* [[List of films featuring surveillance]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=N}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"CastRousey\">{{cite news|first=Justin |last=Kroll |url=https://variety.com/2013/film/news/ufc-ronda-rousey-fast-7-1200567565/ |title=UFC Star Ronda Rousey Gears Up for 'Fast & Furious 7' (EXCLUSIVE) |publisher=[[PMC (company)|PMC]] |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=August 7, 2013 |accessdate=August 7, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6IiIyquGd?url=http://variety.com/2013/film/news/ufc-ronda-rousey-fast-7-1200567565/ |archivedate=August 8, 2013 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Sequel1\">{{cite news|first=Borys |last=Kit |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/justin-lin-wont-direct-fast-432957 |title=Justin Lin Won't Direct 'Fast & Furious 7' (Exclusive) |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=April 4, 2013 |accessdate=April 4, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6FdIzBv4n?url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/justin-lin-wont-direct-fast-432957 |archived